attach.desc: Gives the address of an associated document for the event.

categories.desc: Gives the name of a category or tag that the event could be classified as.

class.desc: Gives the access classification of the information regarding the event.

comment.desc: Gives a comment regarding the event.

contact.desc: Gives the contact information for the event.

created.desc: Gives the date and time at which the event information was first created in a calendaring system.

description.desc: Gives a detailed description of the event.

dtend.desc: Gives the date and time by which the event ends.

dtstart.desc: Gives the date and time at which the event starts.

duration.desc: Gives the duration of the event.

exdate.desc: Gives a date and time at which the event does not occur despite the recurrence rules.

geo.desc: Gives the geographical position of the event.

last-modified.desc: Gives the date and time at which the event information was last modified in a calendaring system.

location.desc: Gives the location of the event.

rdate.desc: Gives a date and time at which the event recurs.

resources.desc: Gives a resource that will be needed for the event.

rrule.desc: Gives a rule for finding dates and times at which the event occurs.

sequence.desc: Gives a revision number for the event information.

status.desc: Gives the confirmation status of the event.

summary.desc: Gives a short summary of the event.

transp.desc: Gives whether the event is to be considered as consuming time on a calendar, for the purpose of free-busy time searches.

uid.desc: Gives a globally unique identifier corresponding to the event.

url.desc: Gives a URL for the event.

http://microformats.org/profile/hcard.desc: A person's or organization's contact information.
http://microformats.org/profile/hcard.label: vCard

adr.desc: Gives the delivery address of the person or organization.

country-name.desc: Gives the country name component of the delivery address of the person or organization.

extended-address.desc: Gives an additional component of the delivery address of the person or organization.

locality.desc: Gives the locality component (e.g. city) of the delivery address of the person or organization.

post-office-box.desc: Gives the post office box component of the delivery address of the person or organization.

postal-code.desc: Gives the postal code component of the delivery address of the person or organization.

region.desc: Gives the region component (e.g. state or province) of the delivery address of the person or organization.

street-address.desc: Gives the street address component of the delivery address of the person or organization.

type.desc: Gives the type of delivery address.

home.desc: Indicates a delivery address for a residence.

work.desc: Indicates a delivery address for a place of work.

agent.desc: Gives the contact information of another person who will act on behalf of the person or organization.

anniversary.desc: Gives the birth date of the person or organization.

bday.desc: Gives the birth date of the person or organization.

categories.desc: Gives the name of a category or tag that the person or organization could be classified as.

email.desc: Gives the e-mail address of the person or organization.

fn.desc: Gives the formatted text corresponding to the name of the person or organization.

gender-identity.desc: Gives the gender identity of the person.

geo.desc: Gives the geographical position of the person or organization.

impp.desc: Gives a URL for instant messaging and presence protocol communications with the person or organization.

kind.desc: Describes what kind of contact the item represents.

group.desc: Indicates multiple entities (e.g. a mailing list).

individual.desc: Indicates a single entity (e.g. a person).

location.desc: Indicates a geographical place (e.g. an office building).

org.desc: Indicates a single entity that is not a person (e.g. a company).

lang.desc: Gives a language understood by the person or organization.

logo.desc: Gives the logo of the person or organization.

member.desc: Gives a URL that represents a member of the group.

n.desc: Gives the structured name of the person or organization.

additional-name.desc: Gives the any additional names of the person.

family-name.desc: Gives the family name of the person, or the full name of the organization.

given-name.desc: Gives the given-name of the person.

honorific-prefix.desc: Gives the honorific prefix of the person.

honorific-suffix.desc: Gives the honorific suffix of the person.

nickname.desc: Gives the nickname of the person or organization.

note.desc: Gives supplemental information or a comment about the person or organization.

org.desc: Gives the name and units of the organization.

organization-name.desc: Gives the name of the organization.

organization-unit.desc: Gives the name of the organization unit.

photo.desc: Gives a photograph of the person or organization.

related.desc: Gives a relationship to another entity.

rel.desc: Gives the relationship between the entity and the related entity.

agent.desc: Another entity that acts on behalf of this entity.

url.desc: Gives the URL for the related entity.

rev.desc: Gives the revision date and time of the contact information.

role.desc: Gives the role, occupation, or business category of the person or organization.

sex.desc: Gives the biological sex of the person.

sound.desc: Gives a sound file relating to the person or organization.

tel.desc: Gives the telephone number of the person or organization.

type.desc: Gives the type of telephone number.

pager.desc: Indicates a paging device telephone number.

text.desc: Indicates that the telephone number supports text messages (SMS).

textphone.desc: Indicates a telecommunication device for people with hearing or speech difficulties.

video.desc: Indicates a video conferencing telephone number.

work.desc: Indicates a telephone number for a place of work.

value.desc: Gives the actual telephone number of the person or organization.

title.desc: Gives the job title, functional position or function of the person or organization.

tz.desc: Gives the time zone of the person or organization.

uid.desc: Gives a globally unique identifier corresponding to the person or organization.

url.desc: Gives a URL relating to the person or organization.

http://n.whatwg.org/work.desc: A work (e.g. an article, an image, a video, a song, etc).
http://n.whatwg.org/work.label: Licensing works

author.desc: Gives the name or contact information of one of the authors or creators of the work.

license.desc: Identifies one of the licenses under which the work is available.

title.desc: Gives the name of the work.

http://schema.org/AMRadioChannel.desc: A radio channel that uses AM.

http://schema.org/APIReference.desc: Reference documentation for application programming interfaces (APIs).

assembly.desc: Library file name e.g., mscorlib.dll, system.web.dll.

executableLibraryName.desc: Library file name e.g., mscorlib.dll, system.web.dll.

programmingModel.desc: Indicates whether API is managed or unmanaged.

targetPlatform.desc: Type of app development: phone, Metro style, desktop, XBox, etc.

http://schema.org/AcceptAction.desc:
The act of committing to/adopting an object.

Related actions:

* [[RejectAction]]: The antonym of AcceptAction.

http://schema.org/Accommodation.desc:
An accommodation is a place that can accommodate human beings, e.g. a hotel room, a camping pitch, or a meeting room. Many accommodations are for overnight stays, but this is not a mandatory requirement.
For more specific types of accommodations not defined in schema.org, one can use additionalType with external vocabularies.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

amenityFeature.desc: An amenity feature (e.g. a characteristic or service) of the Accommodation. This generic property does not make a statement about whether the feature is included in an offer for the main accommodation or available at extra costs.

floorSize.desc:
The size of the accommodation, e.g. in square meter or squarefoot.
Typical unit code(s): MTK for square meter, FTK for square foot, or YDK for square yard

numberOfRooms.desc:
The number of rooms (excluding bathrooms and closets) of the accommodation or lodging business.
Typical unit code(s): ROM for room or C62 for no unit. The type of room can be put in the unitText property of the QuantitativeValue.

permittedUsage.desc: Indications regarding the permitted usage of the accommodation.

petsAllowed.desc: Indicates whether pets are allowed to enter the accommodation or lodging business. More detailed information can be put in a text value.

http://schema.org/AccountingService.desc: Accountancy business.\n\nAs a [[LocalBusiness]] it can be described as a [[provider]] of one or more [[Service]]\(s).

http://schema.org/AchieveAction.desc: The act of accomplishing something via previous efforts. It is an instantaneous action rather than an ongoing process.

http://schema.org/Action.desc: An action performed by a direct agent and indirect participants upon a direct object. Optionally happens at a location with the help of an inanimate instrument. The execution of the action may produce a result. Specific action sub-type documentation specifies the exact expectation of each argument/role.\n\nSee also [blog post](http://blog.schema.org/2014/04/announcing-schemaorg-actions.html) and [Actions overview document](http://schema.org/docs/actions.html).

actionStatus.desc: Indicates the current disposition of the Action.

agent.desc: The direct performer or driver of the action (animate or inanimate). e.g. *John* wrote a book.

endTime.desc: The endTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to end. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from January to *December*. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the end of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

error.desc: For failed actions, more information on the cause of the failure.

instrument.desc: The object that helped the agent perform the action. e.g. John wrote a book with *a pen*.

location.desc: The location of for example where the event is happening, an organization is located, or where an action takes place.

object.desc: The object upon which the action is carried out, whose state is kept intact or changed. Also known as the semantic roles patient, affected or undergoer (which change their state) or theme (which doesn't). e.g. John read *a book*.

participant.desc: Other co-agents that participated in the action indirectly. e.g. John wrote a book with *Steve*.

result.desc: The result produced in the action. e.g. John wrote *a book*.

startTime.desc: The startTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to start. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from *January* to December. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the start of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

target.desc: Indicates a target EntryPoint for an Action.

http://schema.org/ActionAccessSpecificat.desc: A set of requirements that a must be fulfilled in order to perform an Action.

availabilityEnds.desc: The end of the availability of the product or service included in the offer.

availabilityStarts.desc: The beginning of the availability of the product or service included in the offer.

category.desc: A category for the item. Greater signs or slashes can be used to informally indicate a category hierarchy.

eligibleRegion.desc: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is valid.\n\nSee also [[ineligibleRegion]].

expectsAcceptanceOf.desc: An Offer which must be accepted before the user can perform the Action. For example, the user may need to buy a movie before being able to watch it.

requiresSubscription.desc: Indicates if use of the media require a subscription  (either paid or free). Allowed values are ```true``` or ```false``` (note that an earlier version had 'yes', 'no').

http://schema.org/ActivateAction.desc: The act of starting or activating a device or application (e.g. starting a timer or turning on a flashlight).

http://schema.org/AddAction.desc: The act of editing by adding an object to a collection.

http://schema.org/AdministrativeArea.desc: A geographical region, typically under the jurisdiction of a particular government.

http://schema.org/AggregateOffer.desc: When a single product is associated with multiple offers (for example, the same pair of shoes is offered by different merchants), then AggregateOffer can be used.

highPrice.desc:
The highest price of all offers available.

Usage guidelines:

* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.

lowPrice.desc:
The lowest price of all offers available.

Usage guidelines:

* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.

offerCount.desc: The number of offers for the product.

offers.desc: An offer to provide this itemfor example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event.

http://schema.org/AggregateRating.desc: The average rating based on multiple ratings or reviews.

itemReviewed.desc: The item that is being reviewed/rated.

ratingCount.desc: The count of total number of ratings.

reviewCount.desc: The count of total number of reviews.

http://schema.org/AgreeAction.desc: The act of expressing a consistency of opinion with the object. An agent agrees to/about an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.

http://schema.org/Airline.desc: An organization that provides flights for passengers.

boardingPolicy.desc: The type of boarding policy used by the airline (e.g. zone-based or group-based).

iataCode.desc: IATA identifier for an airline or airport.
IATA identifier for an airline or airport.

http://schema.org/AlignmentObject.desc: An intangible item that describes an alignment between a learning resource and a node in an educational framework.

alignmentType.desc: A category of alignment between the learning resource and the framework node. Recommended values include: 'assesses', 'teaches', 'requires', 'textComplexity', 'readingLevel', 'educationalSubject', and 'educationalLevel'.

educationalFramework.desc: The framework to which the resource being described is aligned.

targetDescription.desc: The description of a node in an established educational framework.

targetName.desc: The name of a node in an established educational framework.

targetUrl.desc: The URL of a node in an established educational framework.

http://schema.org/AllocateAction.desc: The act of organizing tasks/objects/events by associating resources to it.

http://schema.org/Answer.desc: An answer offered to a question; perhaps correct, perhaps opinionated or wrong.

http://schema.org/Apartment.desc: An apartment (in American English) or flat (in British English) is a self-contained housing unit (a type of residential real estate) that occupies only part of a building (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apartment).

numberOfRooms.desc:
The number of rooms (excluding bathrooms and closets) of the accommodation or lodging business.
Typical unit code(s): ROM for room or C62 for no unit. The type of room can be put in the unitText property of the QuantitativeValue.

occupancy.desc:
The allowed total occupancy for the accommodation in persons (including infants etc). For individual accommodations, this is not necessarily the legal maximum but defines the permitted usage as per the contractual agreement (e.g. a double room used by a single person).
Typical unit code(s): C62 for person

http://schema.org/AppendAction.desc: The act of inserting at the end if an ordered collection.

http://schema.org/ApplyAction.desc:
The act of registering to an organization/service without the guarantee to receive it.

Related actions:

* [[RegisterAction]]: Unlike RegisterAction, ApplyAction has no guarantees that the application will be accepted.

http://schema.org/ArriveAction.desc: The act of arriving at a place. An agent arrives at a destination from a fromLocation, optionally with participants.

http://schema.org/Article.desc: An article, such as a news article or piece of investigative report. Newspapers and magazines have articles of many different types and this is intended to cover them all.\n\nSee also [blog post](http://blog.schema.org/2014/09/schemaorg-support-for-bibliographic_2.html).

articleBody.desc: The actual body of the article.

articleSection.desc: Articles may belong to one or more 'sections' in a magazine or newspaper, such as Sports, Lifestyle, etc.

pageEnd.desc: The page on which the work ends; for example "138" or "xvi".

pageStart.desc: The page on which the work starts; for example "135" or "xiii".

pagination.desc: Any description of pages that is not separated into pageStart and pageEnd; for example, "1-6, 9, 55" or "10-12, 46-49".

speakable.desc:
Indicates sections of a Web page that are particularly 'speakable' in the sense of being highlighted as being especially appropriate for text-to-speech conversion. Other sections of a page may also be usefully spoken in particular circumstances; the 'speakable' property serves to indicate the parts most likely to be generally useful for speech.

The *speakable* property can be repeated an arbitrary number of times, with three kinds of possible 'content-locator' values:

1.) *id-value* URL references - uses *id-value* of an element in the page being annotated. The simplest use of *speakable* has (potentially relative) URL values, referencing identified sections of the document concerned.

2.) CSS Selectors - addresses content in the annotated page, eg. via class attribute. Use the [[cssSelector]] property.

3.)  XPaths - addresses content via XPaths (assuming an XML view of the content). Use the [[xpath]] property.


For more sophisticated markup of speakable sections beyond simple ID references, either CSS selectors or XPath expressions to pick out document section(s) as speakable. For this
we define a supporting type, [[SpeakableSpecification]]  which is defined to be a possible value of the *speakable* property.

wordCount.desc: The number of words in the text of the Article.

http://schema.org/AskAction.desc:
The act of posing a question / favor to someone.

Related actions:

* [[ReplyAction]]: Appears generally as a response to AskAction.

question.desc: A sub property of object. A question.

http://schema.org/AssessAction.desc: The act of forming one's opinion, reaction or sentiment.

http://schema.org/AssignAction.desc: The act of allocating an action/event/task to some destination (someone or something).

http://schema.org/Attorney.desc: Professional service: Attorney. \n\nThis type is deprecated - [[LegalService]] is more inclusive and less ambiguous.

http://schema.org/Audience.desc: Intended audience for an item, i.e. the group for whom the item was created.

audienceType.desc: The target group associated with a given audience (e.g. veterans, car owners, musicians, etc.).

geographicArea.desc: The geographic area associated with the audience.

caption.desc: The caption for this object. For downloadable machine formats (closed caption, subtitles etc.) use MediaObject and indicate the [[encodingFormat]].

transcript.desc: If this MediaObject is an AudioObject or VideoObject, the transcript of that object.

http://schema.org/AuthorizeAction.desc: The act of granting permission to an object.

recipient.desc: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

http://schema.org/BankAccount.desc: A product or service offered by a bank whereby one may deposit, withdraw or transfer money and in some cases be paid interest.

http://schema.org/Barcode.desc: An image of a visual machine-readable code such as a barcode or QR code.

http://schema.org/BedAndBreakfast.desc:
Bed and breakfast.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

http://schema.org/BedDetails.desc: An entity holding detailed information about the available bed types, e.g. the quantity of twin beds for a hotel room. For the single case of just one bed of a certain type, you can use bed directly with a text. See also [[BedType]] (under development).

numberOfBeds.desc: The quantity of the given bed type available in the HotelRoom, Suite, House, or Apartment.

typeOfBed.desc: The type of bed to which the BedDetail refers, i.e. the type of bed available in the quantity indicated by quantity.

http://schema.org/BedType.desc: A type of bed. This is used for indicating the bed or beds available in an accommodation.

http://schema.org/BefriendAction.desc:
The act of forming a personal connection with someone (object) mutually/bidirectionally/symmetrically.

Related actions:

* [[FollowAction]]: Unlike FollowAction, BefriendAction implies that the connection is reciprocal.

blogPost.desc: A posting that is part of this blog.

blogPosts.desc: The postings that are part of this blog.

issn.desc: The International Standard Serial Number (ISSN) that identifies this serial publication. You can repeat this property to identify different formats of, or the linking ISSN (ISSN-L) for, this serial publication.

http://schema.org/BoardingPolicyType.desc: A type of boarding policy used by an airline.

http://schema.org/BodyOfWater.desc: A body of water, such as a sea, ocean, or lake.

numberOfPages.desc: The number of pages in the book.

http://schema.org/BookFormatType.desc: The publication format of the book.

http://schema.org/BookSeries.desc: A series of books. Included books can be indicated with the hasPart property.

http://schema.org/BorrowAction.desc:
The act of obtaining an object under an agreement to return it at a later date. Reciprocal of LendAction.

Related actions:

* [[LendAction]]: Reciprocal of BorrowAction.

lender.desc: A sub property of participant. The person that lends the object being borrowed.

http://schema.org/Brand.desc: A brand is a name used by an organization or business person for labeling a product, product group, or similar.

aggregateRating.desc: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

slogan.desc: A slogan or motto associated with the item.

http://schema.org/BreadcrumbList.desc: A BreadcrumbList is an ItemList consisting of a chain of linked Web pages, typically described using at least their URL and their name, and typically ending with the current page.\n\nThe [[position]] property is used to reconstruct the order of the items in a BreadcrumbList The convention is that a breadcrumb list has an [[itemListOrder]] of [[ItemListOrderAscending]] (lower values listed first), and that the first items in this list correspond to the "top" or beginning of the breadcrumb trail, e.g. with a site or section homepage. The specific values of 'position' are not assigned meaning for a BreadcrumbList, but they should be integers, e.g. beginning with '1' for the first item in the list.

http://schema.org/BroadcastChannel.desc: A unique instance of a BroadcastService on a CableOrSatelliteService lineup.

broadcastChannelId.desc: The unique address by which the BroadcastService can be identified in a provider lineup. In US, this is typically a number.

broadcastFrequency.desc: The frequency used for over-the-air broadcasts. Numeric values or simple ranges e.g. 87-99. In addition a shortcut idiom is supported for frequences of AM and FM radio channels, e.g. "87 FM".

broadcastServiceTier.desc: The type of service required to have access to the channel (e.g. Standard or Premium).

genre.desc: Genre of the creative work, broadcast channel or group.

providesBroadcastService.desc: The BroadcastService offered on this channel.

http://schema.org/BroadcastEvent.desc: An over the air or online broadcast event.

broadcastOfEvent.desc: The event being broadcast such as a sporting event or awards ceremony.

isLiveBroadcast.desc: True is the broadcast is of a live event.

videoFormat.desc: The type of screening or video broadcast used (e.g. IMAX, 3D, SD, HD, etc.).

http://schema.org/BroadcastFrequencySpec.desc: The frequency in MHz and the modulation used for a particular BroadcastService.

broadcastFrequencyValue.desc: The frequency in MHz for a particular broadcast.

http://schema.org/BroadcastService.desc: A delivery service through which content is provided via broadcast over the air or online.

area.desc: The area within which users can expect to reach the broadcast service.

broadcastAffiliateOf.desc: The media network(s) whose content is broadcast on this station.

broadcastDisplayName.desc: The name displayed in the channel guide. For many US affiliates, it is the network name.

broadcastFrequency.desc: The frequency used for over-the-air broadcasts. Numeric values or simple ranges e.g. 87-99. In addition a shortcut idiom is supported for frequences of AM and FM radio channels, e.g. "87 FM".

broadcastTimezone.desc: The timezone in [ISO 8601 format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601) for which the service bases its broadcasts

broadcaster.desc: The organization owning or operating the broadcast service.

hasBroadcastChannel.desc: A broadcast channel of a broadcast service.

parentService.desc: A broadcast service to which the broadcast service may belong to such as regional variations of a national channel.

videoFormat.desc: The type of screening or video broadcast used (e.g. IMAX, 3D, SD, HD, etc.).

http://schema.org/BusReservation.desc: A reservation for bus travel. \n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, use [[Offer]].

http://schema.org/BusTrip.desc: A trip on a commercial bus line.

arrivalBusStop.desc: The stop or station from which the bus arrives.

busName.desc: The name of the bus (e.g. Bolt Express).

busNumber.desc: The unique identifier for the bus.

departureBusStop.desc: The stop or station from which the bus departs.

http://schema.org/BusinessAudience.desc: A set of characteristics belonging to businesses, e.g. who compose an item's target audience.

numberOfEmployees.desc: The number of employees in an organization e.g. business.

yearlyRevenue.desc: The size of the business in annual revenue.

http://schema.org/BusinessEntityType.desc:
A business entity type is a conceptual entity representing the legal form, the size, the main line of business, the position in the value chain, or any combination thereof, of an organization or business person.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Business
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Enduser
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PublicInstitution
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Reseller

http://schema.org/BusinessFunction.desc:
The business function specifies the type of activity or access (i.e., the bundle of rights) offered by the organization or business person through the offer. Typical are sell, rental or lease, maintenance or repair, manufacture / produce, recycle / dispose, engineering / construction, or installation. Proprietary specifications of access rights are also instances of this class.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ConstructionInstallation
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Dispose
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#LeaseOut
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Maintain
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ProvideService
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Repair
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Buy

http://schema.org/BuyAction.desc: The act of giving money to a seller in exchange for goods or services rendered. An agent buys an object, product, or service from a seller for a price. Reciprocal of SellAction.

seller.desc: An entity which offers (sells / leases / lends / loans) the services / goods.  A seller may also be a provider.

warrantyPromise.desc: The warranty promise(s) included in the offer.

http://schema.org/CableOrSatelliteServic.desc: A service which provides access to media programming like TV or radio. Access may be via cable or satellite.

http://schema.org/Campground.desc:
A camping site, campsite, or [[Campground]] is a place used for overnight stay in the outdoors, typically containing individual [[CampingPitch]] locations. \n\n
In British English a campsite is an area, usually divided into a number of pitches, where people can camp overnight using tents or camper vans or caravans; this British English use of the word is synonymous with the American English expression campground. In American English the term campsite generally means an area where an individual, family, group, or military unit can pitch a tent or park a camper; a campground may contain many campsites (Source: Wikipedia see [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campsite](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campsite)).\n\n

See also the dedicated [document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations](/docs/hotels.html).

http://schema.org/CampingPitch.desc:
A [[CampingPitch]] is an individual place for overnight stay in the outdoors, typically being part of a larger camping site, or [[Campground]].\n\n      
In British English a campsite, or campground, is an area, usually divided into a number of pitches, where people can camp overnight using tents or camper vans or caravans; this British English use of the word is synonymous with the American English expression campground. In American English the term campsite generally means an area where an individual, family, group, or military unit can pitch a tent or park a camper; a campground may contain many campsites.
(Source: Wikipedia see [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campsite](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campsite)).\n\n
See also the dedicated [document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations](/docs/hotels.html).

http://schema.org/Canal.desc: A canal, like the Panama Canal.

http://schema.org/CancelAction.desc:
The act of asserting that a future event/action is no longer going to happen.

Related actions:

* [[ConfirmAction]]: The antonym of CancelAction.

http://schema.org/Car.desc: A car is a wheeled, self-powered motor vehicle used for transportation.

http://schema.org/CheckAction.desc: An agent inspects, determines, investigates, inquires, or examines an object's accuracy, quality, condition, or state.

http://schema.org/CheckInAction.desc:
The act of an agent communicating (service provider, social media, etc) their arrival by registering/confirming for a previously reserved service (e.g. flight check in) or at a place (e.g. hotel), possibly resulting in a result (boarding pass, etc).

Related actions:

* [[CheckOutAction]]: The antonym of CheckInAction.
* [[ArriveAction]]: Unlike ArriveAction, CheckInAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the start of a previously reserved service.
* [[ConfirmAction]]: Unlike ConfirmAction, CheckInAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the *start* of a previously reserved service rather than its validity/existence.

http://schema.org/CheckOutAction.desc:
The act of an agent communicating (service provider, social media, etc) their departure of a previously reserved service (e.g. flight check in) or place (e.g. hotel).

Related actions:

* [[CheckInAction]]: The antonym of CheckOutAction.
* [[DepartAction]]: Unlike DepartAction, CheckOutAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the end of a previously reserved service.
* [[CancelAction]]: Unlike CancelAction, CheckOutAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the end of a previously reserved service.

http://schema.org/ChooseAction.desc: The act of expressing a preference from a set of options or a large or unbounded set of choices/options.

actionOption.desc: A sub property of object. The options subject to this action.

option.desc: A sub property of object. The options subject to this action.

http://schema.org/CivicStructure.desc: A public structure, such as a town hall or concert hall.

openingHours.desc:
The general opening hours for a business. Opening hours can be specified as a weekly time range, starting with days, then times per day. Multiple days can be listed with commas ',' separating each day. Day or time ranges are specified using a hyphen '-'.

* Days are specified using the following two-letter combinations: ```Mo```, ```Tu```, ```We```, ```Th```, ```Fr```, ```Sa```, ```Su```.
* Times are specified using 24:00 time. For example, 3pm is specified as ```15:00```. 
* Here is an example: <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Tu,Th 16:00-20:00">Tuesdays and Thursdays 4-8pm</time>.
* If a business is open 7 days a week, then it can be specified as <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Mo-Su">Monday through Sunday, all day</time>.

http://schema.org/ClaimReview.desc: A fact-checking review of claims made (or reported) in some creative work (referenced via itemReviewed).

claimReviewed.desc: A short summary of the specific claims reviewed in a ClaimReview.

http://schema.org/Clip.desc: A short TV or radio program or a segment/part of a program.

actor.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

actors.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

clipNumber.desc: Position of the clip within an ordered group of clips.

director.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

directors.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

partOfEpisode.desc: The episode to which this clip belongs.

partOfSeason.desc: The season to which this episode belongs.

partOfSeries.desc: The series to which this episode or season belongs.

http://schema.org/Code.desc: Computer programming source code. Example: Full (compile ready) solutions, code snippet samples, scripts, templates.

http://schema.org/CollegeOrUniversity.desc: A college, university, or other third-level educational institution.

http://schema.org/Comment.desc: A comment on an item - for example, a comment on a blog post. The comment's content is expressed via the [[text]] property, and its topic via [[about]], properties shared with all CreativeWorks.

downvoteCount.desc: The number of downvotes this question, answer or comment has received from the community.

parentItem.desc: The parent of a question, answer or item in general.

upvoteCount.desc: The number of upvotes this question, answer or comment has received from the community.

http://schema.org/CommentAction.desc: The act of generating a comment about a subject.

resultComment.desc: A sub property of result. The Comment created or sent as a result of this action.

http://schema.org/CommunicateAction.desc: The act of conveying information to another person via a communication medium (instrument) such as speech, email, or telephone conversation.

about.desc: The subject matter of the content.

inLanguage.desc: The language of the content or performance or used in an action. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[availableLanguage]].

language.desc: A sub property of instrument. The language used on this action.

recipient.desc: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

http://schema.org/CompoundPriceSpecifica.desc: A compound price specification is one that bundles multiple prices that all apply in combination for different dimensions of consumption. Use the name property of the attached unit price specification for indicating the dimension of a price component (e.g. "electricity" or "final cleaning").

priceComponent.desc: This property links to all [[UnitPriceSpecification]] nodes that apply in parallel for the [[CompoundPriceSpecification]] node.

http://schema.org/ComputerLanguage.desc: This type covers computer programming languages such as Scheme and Lisp, as well as other language-like computer representations. Natural languages are best represented with the [[Language]] type.

http://schema.org/ConfirmAction.desc:
The act of notifying someone that a future event/action is going to happen as expected.

Related actions:

* [[CancelAction]]: The antonym of ConfirmAction.

actionAccessibilityRequirement.desc: A set of requirements that a must be fulfilled in order to perform an Action. If more than one value is specied, fulfilling one set of requirements will allow the Action to be performed.

expectsAcceptanceOf.desc: An Offer which must be accepted before the user can perform the Action. For example, the user may need to buy a movie before being able to watch it.

http://schema.org/ContactPoint.desc: A contact pointfor example, a Customer Complaints department.

areaServed.desc: The geographic area where a service or offered item is provided.

availableLanguage.desc: A language someone may use with or at the item, service or place. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[inLanguage]]

contactOption.desc: An option available on this contact point (e.g. a toll-free number or support for hearing-impaired callers).

contactType.desc: A person or organization can have different contact points, for different purposes. For example, a sales contact point, a PR contact point and so on. This property is used to specify the kind of contact point.

hoursAvailable.desc: The hours during which this service or contact is available.

productSupported.desc: The product or service this support contact point is related to (such as product support for a particular product line). This can be a specific product or product line (e.g. "iPhone") or a general category of products or services (e.g. "smartphones").

serviceArea.desc: The geographic area where the service is provided.

http://schema.org/ContactPointOption.desc: Enumerated options related to a ContactPoint.

http://schema.org/Continent.desc: One of the continents (for example, Europe or Africa).

http://schema.org/ControlAction.desc: An agent controls a device or application.

http://schema.org/Conversation.desc: One or more messages between organizations or people on a particular topic. Individual messages can be linked to the conversation with isPartOf or hasPart properties.

foodEstablishment.desc: A sub property of location. The specific food establishment where the action occurred.

foodEvent.desc: A sub property of location. The specific food event where the action occurred.

recipe.desc: A sub property of instrument. The recipe/instructions used to perform the action.

tickerSymbol.desc: The exchange traded instrument associated with a Corporation object. The tickerSymbol is expressed as an exchange and an instrument name separated by a space character. For the exchange component of the tickerSymbol attribute, we recommend using the controlled vocabulary of Market Identifier Codes (MIC) specified in ISO15022.

http://schema.org/Course.desc: A description of an educational course which may be offered as distinct instances at which take place at different times or take place at different locations, or be offered through different media or modes of study. An educational course is a sequence of one or more educational events and/or creative works which aims to build knowledge, competence or ability of learners.

courseCode.desc: The identifier for the [[Course]] used by the course [[provider]] (e.g. CS101 or 6.001).

coursePrerequisites.desc: Requirements for taking the Course. May be completion of another [[Course]] or a textual description like "permission of instructor". Requirements may be a pre-requisite competency, referenced using [[AlignmentObject]].

hasCourseInstance.desc: An offering of the course at a specific time and place or through specific media or mode of study or to a specific section of students.

http://schema.org/CourseInstance.desc: An instance of a [[Course]] which is distinct from other instances because it is offered at a different time or location or through different media or modes of study or to a specific section of students.

courseMode.desc: The medium or means of delivery of the course instance or the mode of study, either as a text label (e.g. "online", "onsite" or "blended"; "synchronous" or "asynchronous"; "full-time" or "part-time") or as a URL reference to a term from a controlled vocabulary (e.g. https://ceds.ed.gov/element/001311#Asynchronous ).

instructor.desc: A person assigned to instruct or provide instructional assistance for the [[CourseInstance]].

http://schema.org/CreateAction.desc: The act of deliberately creating/producing/generating/building a result out of the agent.

http://schema.org/CreativeWork.desc: The most generic kind of creative work, including books, movies, photographs, software programs, etc.

about.desc: The subject matter of the content.

accessMode.desc: The human sensory perceptual system or cognitive faculty through which a person may process or perceive information. Expected values include: auditory, tactile, textual, visual, colorDependent, chartOnVisual, chemOnVisual, diagramOnVisual, mathOnVisual, musicOnVisual, textOnVisual.

accessModeSufficient.desc: A list of single or combined accessModes that are sufficient to understand all the intellectual content of a resource. Expected values include:  auditory, tactile, textual, visual.

accessibilityAPI.desc: Indicates that the resource is compatible with the referenced accessibility API.

accessibilityControl.desc: Identifies input methods that are sufficient to fully control the described resource.

accessibilityFeature.desc: Content features of the resource, such as accessible media, alternatives and supported enhancements for accessibility.

accessibilityHazard.desc: A characteristic of the described resource that is physiologically dangerous to some users. Related to WCAG 2.0 guideline 2.3.

accessibilitySummary.desc: A human-readable summary of specific accessibility features or deficiencies, consistent with the other accessibility metadata but expressing subtleties such as "short descriptions are present but long descriptions will be needed for non-visual users" or "short descriptions are present and no long descriptions are needed."

accountablePerson.desc: Specifies the Person that is legally accountable for the CreativeWork.

aggregateRating.desc: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

alternativeHeadline.desc: A secondary title of the CreativeWork.

associatedMedia.desc: A media object that encodes this CreativeWork. This property is a synonym for encoding.

audience.desc: An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.

author.desc: The author of this content or rating. Please note that author is special in that HTML 5 provides a special mechanism for indicating authorship via the rel tag. That is equivalent to this and may be used interchangeably.

award.desc: An award won by or for this item.

awards.desc: Awards won by or for this item.

character.desc: Fictional person connected with a creative work.

citation.desc: A citation or reference to another creative work, such as another publication, web page, scholarly article, etc.

commentCount.desc: The number of comments this CreativeWork (e.g. Article, Question or Answer) has received. This is most applicable to works published in Web sites with commenting system; additional comments may exist elsewhere.

contentLocation.desc: The location depicted or described in the content. For example, the location in a photograph or painting.

contentRating.desc: Official rating of a piece of contentfor example,'MPAA PG-13'.

contributor.desc: A secondary contributor to the CreativeWork or Event.

copyrightHolder.desc: The party holding the legal copyright to the CreativeWork.

copyrightYear.desc: The year during which the claimed copyright for the CreativeWork was first asserted.

creator.desc: The creator/author of this CreativeWork. This is the same as the Author property for CreativeWork.

dateCreated.desc: The date on which the CreativeWork was created or the item was added to a DataFeed.

dateModified.desc: The date on which the CreativeWork was most recently modified or when the item's entry was modified within a DataFeed.

discussionUrl.desc: A link to the page containing the comments of the CreativeWork.

editor.desc: Specifies the Person who edited the CreativeWork.

educationalAlignment.desc: An alignment to an established educational framework.

educationalUse.desc: The purpose of a work in the context of education; for example, 'assignment', 'group work'.

encoding.desc: A media object that encodes this CreativeWork. This property is a synonym for associatedMedia.

encodingFormat.desc:
Media type typically expressed using a MIME format (see [IANA site](http://www.iana.org/assignments/media-types/media-types.xhtml) and [MDN reference](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Basics_of_HTTP/MIME_types)) e.g. application/zip for a SoftwareApplication binary, audio/mpeg for .mp3 etc.).

In cases where a [[CreativeWork]] has several media type representations, [[encoding]] can be used to indicate each [[MediaObject]] alongside particular [[encodingFormat]] information.

Unregistered or niche encoding and file formats can be indicated instead via the most appropriate URL, e.g. defining Web page or a Wikipedia/Wikidata entry.

encodings.desc: A media object that encodes this CreativeWork.

exampleOfWork.desc: A creative work that this work is an example/instance/realization/derivation of.

expires.desc: Date the content expires and is no longer useful or available. For example a [[VideoObject]] or [[NewsArticle]] whose availability or relevance is time-limited, or a [[ClaimReview]] fact check whose publisher wants to indicate that it may no longer be relevant (or helpful to highlight) after some date.

fileFormat.desc: Media type, typically MIME format (see [IANA site](http://www.iana.org/assignments/media-types/media-types.xhtml)) of the content e.g. application/zip of a SoftwareApplication binary. In cases where a CreativeWork has several media type representations, 'encoding' can be used to indicate each MediaObject alongside particular fileFormat information. Unregistered or niche file formats can be indicated instead via the most appropriate URL, e.g. defining Web page or a Wikipedia entry.

funder.desc: A person or organization that supports (sponsors) something through some kind of financial contribution.

genre.desc: Genre of the creative work, broadcast channel or group.

hasPart.desc: Indicates an item or CreativeWork that is part of this item, or CreativeWork (in some sense).

inLanguage.desc: The language of the content or performance or used in an action. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[availableLanguage]].

interactionStatistic.desc: The number of interactions for the CreativeWork using the WebSite or SoftwareApplication. The most specific child type of InteractionCounter should be used.

interactivityType.desc: The predominant mode of learning supported by the learning resource. Acceptable values are 'active', 'expositive', or 'mixed'.

isAccessibleForFree.desc: A flag to signal that the item, event, or place is accessible for free.

isBasedOn.desc: A resource that was used in the creation of this resource. This term can be repeated for multiple sources. For example, http://example.com/great-multiplication-intro.html.

isBasedOnUrl.desc: A resource that was used in the creation of this resource. This term can be repeated for multiple sources. For example, http://example.com/great-multiplication-intro.html.

isFamilyFriendly.desc: Indicates whether this content is family friendly.

isPartOf.desc: Indicates an item or CreativeWork that this item, or CreativeWork (in some sense), is part of.

keywords.desc: Keywords or tags used to describe this content. Multiple entries in a keywords list are typically delimited by commas.

learningResourceType.desc: The predominant type or kind characterizing the learning resource. For example, 'presentation', 'handout'.

license.desc: A license document that applies to this content, typically indicated by URL.

locationCreated.desc: The location where the CreativeWork was created, which may not be the same as the location depicted in the CreativeWork.

mainEntity.desc: Indicates the primary entity described in some page or other CreativeWork.

material.desc: A material that something is made from, e.g. leather, wool, cotton, paper.

mentions.desc: Indicates that the CreativeWork contains a reference to, but is not necessarily about a concept.

offers.desc: An offer to provide this itemfor example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event.

position.desc: The position of an item in a series or sequence of items.

producer.desc: The person or organization who produced the work (e.g. music album, movie, tv/radio series etc.).

provider.desc: The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.

publication.desc: A publication event associated with the item.

publisher.desc: The publisher of the creative work.

publishingPrinciples.desc:
The publishingPrinciples property indicates (typically via [[URL]]) a document describing the editorial principles of an [[Organization]] (or individual e.g. a [[Person]] writing a blog) that relate to their activities as a publisher, e.g. ethics or diversity policies. When applied to a [[CreativeWork]] (e.g. [[NewsArticle]]) the principles are those of the party primarily responsible for the creation of the [[CreativeWork]].

While such policies are most typically expressed in natural language, sometimes related information (e.g. indicating a [[funder]]) can be expressed using schema.org terminology.

recordedAt.desc: The Event where the CreativeWork was recorded. The CreativeWork may capture all or part of the event.

releasedEvent.desc: The place and time the release was issued, expressed as a PublicationEvent.

schemaVersion.desc: Indicates (by URL or string) a particular version of a schema used in some CreativeWork. For example, a document could declare a schemaVersion using an URL such as http://schema.org/version/2.0/ if precise indication of schema version was required by some application.

sourceOrganization.desc: The Organization on whose behalf the creator was working.

spatial.desc:
The "spatial" property can be used in cases when more specific properties
(e.g. [[locationCreated]], [[spatialCoverage]], [[contentLocation]]) are not known to be appropriate.

spatialCoverage.desc:
The spatialCoverage of a CreativeWork indicates the place(s) which are the focus of the content. It is a subproperty of
      contentLocation intended primarily for more technical and detailed materials. For example with a Dataset, it indicates
      areas that the dataset describes: a dataset of New York weather would have spatialCoverage which was the place: the state of New York.

sponsor.desc: A person or organization that supports a thing through a pledge, promise, or financial contribution. e.g. a sponsor of a Medical Study or a corporate sponsor of an event.

temporal.desc:
The "temporal" property can be used in cases where more specific properties
(e.g. [[temporalCoverage]], [[dateCreated]], [[dateModified]], [[datePublished]]) are not known to be appropriate.

temporalCoverage.desc:
The temporalCoverage of a CreativeWork indicates the period that the content applies to, i.e. that it describes, either as a DateTime or as a textual string indicating a time period in [ISO 8601 time interval format](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601#Time_intervals). In
      the case of a Dataset it will typically indicate the relevant time period in a precise notation (e.g. for a 2011 census dataset, the year 2011 would be written "2011/2012"). Other forms of content e.g. ScholarlyArticle, Book, TVSeries or TVEpisode may indicate their temporalCoverage in broader terms - textually or via well-known URL.
      Written works such as books may sometimes have precise temporal coverage too, e.g. a work set in 1939 - 1945 can be indicated in ISO 8601 interval format format via "1939/1945".

Open-ended date ranges can be written with ".." in place of the end date. For example, "2015-11/.." indicates a range beginning in November 2015 and with no specified final date. This is tentative and might be updated in future when ISO 8601 is officially updated.

text.desc: The textual content of this CreativeWork.

thumbnailUrl.desc: A thumbnail image relevant to the Thing.

timeRequired.desc: Approximate or typical time it takes to work with or through this learning resource for the typical intended target audience, e.g. 'PT30M', 'PT1H25M'.

translator.desc: Organization or person who adapts a creative work to different languages, regional differences and technical requirements of a target market, or that translates during some event.

typicalAgeRange.desc: The typical expected age range, e.g. '7-9', '11-'.

version.desc: The version of the CreativeWork embodied by a specified resource.

workExample.desc: Example/instance/realization/derivation of the concept of this creative work. eg. The paperback edition, first edition, or eBook.

http://schema.org/CreativeWorkSeason.desc: A media season e.g. tv, radio, video game etc.

actor.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

director.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

endDate.desc: The end date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

episode.desc: An episode of a tv, radio or game media within a series or season.

episodes.desc: An episode of a TV/radio series or season.

numberOfEpisodes.desc: The number of episodes in this season or series.

partOfSeries.desc: The series to which this episode or season belongs.

productionCompany.desc: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

seasonNumber.desc: Position of the season within an ordered group of seasons.

startDate.desc: The start date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

trailer.desc: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

http://schema.org/CreativeWorkSeries.desc:
A CreativeWorkSeries in schema.org is a group of related items, typically but not necessarily of the same kind. CreativeWorkSeries are usually organized into some order, often chronological. Unlike [[ItemList]] which is a general purpose data structure for lists of things, the emphasis with CreativeWorkSeries is on published materials (written e.g. books and periodicals, or media such as tv, radio and games).

Specific subtypes are available for describing [[TVSeries]], [[RadioSeries]], [[MovieSeries]], [[BookSeries]], [[Periodical]] and [[VideoGameSeries]]. In each case, the [[hasPart]] / [[isPartOf]] properties can be used to relate the CreativeWorkSeries to its parts. The general CreativeWorkSeries type serves largely just to organize these more specific and practical subtypes.

It is common for properties applicable to an item from the series to be usefully applied to the containing group. Schema.org attempts to anticipate some of these cases, but publishers should be free to apply properties of the series parts to the series as a whole wherever they seem appropriate.

endDate.desc: The end date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

issn.desc: The International Standard Serial Number (ISSN) that identifies this serial publication. You can repeat this property to identify different formats of, or the linking ISSN (ISSN-L) for, this serial publication.

startDate.desc: The start date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

http://schema.org/CreditCard.desc:
A card payment method of a particular brand or name.  Used to mark up a particular payment method and/or the financial product/service that supplies the card account.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#AmericanExpress
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DinersClub
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Discover
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#JCB
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#MasterCard
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#VISA

http://schema.org/CurrencyConversionServ.desc: A service to convert funds from one currency to another currency.

http://schema.org/DanceGroup.desc: A dance groupfor example, the Alvin Ailey Dance Theater or Riverdance.

dataset.desc: A dataset contained in this catalog.

http://schema.org/DataFeed.desc: A single feed providing structured information about one or more entities or topics.

dataFeedElement.desc: An item within in a data feed. Data feeds may have many elements.

http://schema.org/DataFeedItem.desc: A single item within a larger data feed.

dateCreated.desc: The date on which the CreativeWork was created or the item was added to a DataFeed.

dateDeleted.desc: The datetime the item was removed from the DataFeed.

dateModified.desc: The date on which the CreativeWork was most recently modified or when the item's entry was modified within a DataFeed.

item.desc: An entity represented by an entry in a list or data feed (e.g. an 'artist' in a list of 'artists').

http://schema.org/DataType.desc: The basic data types such as Integers, Strings, etc.

http://schema.org/Dataset.desc: A body of structured information describing some topic(s) of interest.

catalog.desc: A data catalog which contains this dataset.

datasetTimeInterval.desc: The range of temporal applicability of a dataset, e.g. for a 2011 census dataset, the year 2011 (in ISO 8601 time interval format).

distribution.desc: A downloadable form of this dataset, at a specific location, in a specific format.

includedDataCatalog.desc: A data catalog which contains this dataset (this property was previously 'catalog', preferred name is now 'includedInDataCatalog').

includedInDataCatalog.desc: A data catalog which contains this dataset.

issn.desc: The International Standard Serial Number (ISSN) that identifies this serial publication. You can repeat this property to identify different formats of, or the linking ISSN (ISSN-L) for, this serial publication.

http://schema.org/DatedMoneySpecificatio.desc: A DatedMoneySpecification represents monetary values with optional start and end dates. For example, this could represent an employee's salary over a specific period of time. __Note:__ This type has been superseded by [[MonetaryAmount]] use of that type is recommended

currency.desc: The currency in which the monetary amount is expressed.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

endDate.desc: The end date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

startDate.desc: The start date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

http://schema.org/DayOfWeek.desc:
The day of the week, e.g. used to specify to which day the opening hours of an OpeningHoursSpecification refer.

Originally, URLs from [GoodRelations](http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1) were used (for [[Monday]], [[Tuesday]], [[Wednesday]], [[Thursday]], [[Friday]], [[Saturday]], [[Sunday]] plus a special entry for [[PublicHolidays]]); these have now been integrated directly into schema.org.

http://schema.org/DeactivateAction.desc: The act of stopping or deactivating a device or application (e.g. stopping a timer or turning off a flashlight).

http://schema.org/DefenceEstablishment.desc: A defence establishment, such as an army or navy base.

http://schema.org/DeleteAction.desc: The act of editing a recipient by removing one of its objects.

http://schema.org/DeliveryChargeSpecific.desc: The price for the delivery of an offer using a particular delivery method.

appliesToDeliveryMethod.desc: The delivery method(s) to which the delivery charge or payment charge specification applies.

areaServed.desc: The geographic area where a service or offered item is provided.

eligibleRegion.desc: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is valid.\n\nSee also [[ineligibleRegion]].

ineligibleRegion.desc: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is not valid, e.g. a region where the transaction is not allowed.\n\nSee also [[eligibleRegion]].

http://schema.org/DeliveryEvent.desc: An event involving the delivery of an item.

accessCode.desc: Password, PIN, or access code needed for delivery (e.g. from a locker).

availableFrom.desc: When the item is available for pickup from the store, locker, etc.

availableThrough.desc: After this date, the item will no longer be available for pickup.

hasDeliveryMethod.desc: Method used for delivery or shipping.

http://schema.org/DeliveryMethod.desc:
A delivery method is a standardized procedure for transferring the product or service to the destination of fulfillment chosen by the customer. Delivery methods are characterized by the means of transportation used, and by the organization or group that is the contracting party for the sending organization or person.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeDirectDownload
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeFreight
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeMail
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeOwnFleet
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModePickUp
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DHL
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#FederalExpress
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#UPS

http://schema.org/Demand.desc: A demand entity represents the public, not necessarily binding, not necessarily exclusive, announcement by an organization or person to seek a certain type of goods or services. For describing demand using this type, the very same properties used for Offer apply.

acceptedPaymentMethod.desc: The payment method(s) accepted by seller for this offer.

advanceBookingRequirement.desc: The amount of time that is required between accepting the offer and the actual usage of the resource or service.

areaServed.desc: The geographic area where a service or offered item is provided.

availability.desc: The availability of this itemfor example In stock, Out of stock, Pre-order, etc.

availabilityEnds.desc: The end of the availability of the product or service included in the offer.

availabilityStarts.desc: The beginning of the availability of the product or service included in the offer.

availableAtOrFrom.desc: The place(s) from which the offer can be obtained (e.g. store locations).

availableDeliveryMethod.desc: The delivery method(s) available for this offer.

businessFunction.desc: The business function (e.g. sell, lease, repair, dispose) of the offer or component of a bundle (TypeAndQuantityNode). The default is http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell.

deliveryLeadTime.desc: The typical delay between the receipt of the order and the goods either leaving the warehouse or being prepared for pickup, in case the delivery method is on site pickup.

eligibleCustomerType.desc: The type(s) of customers for which the given offer is valid.

eligibleDuration.desc: The duration for which the given offer is valid.

eligibleQuantity.desc: The interval and unit of measurement of ordering quantities for which the offer or price specification is valid. This allows e.g. specifying that a certain freight charge is valid only for a certain quantity.

eligibleRegion.desc: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is valid.\n\nSee also [[ineligibleRegion]].

eligibleTransactionVolume.desc: The transaction volume, in a monetary unit, for which the offer or price specification is valid, e.g. for indicating a minimal purchasing volume, to express free shipping above a certain order volume, or to limit the acceptance of credit cards to purchases to a certain minimal amount.

gtin12.desc: The GTIN-12 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. The GTIN-12 is the 12-digit GS1 Identification Key composed of a U.P.C. Company Prefix, Item Reference, and Check Digit used to identify trade items. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

gtin13.desc: The GTIN-13 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This is equivalent to 13-digit ISBN codes and EAN UCC-13. Former 12-digit UPC codes can be converted into a GTIN-13 code by simply adding a preceeding zero. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

gtin14.desc: The GTIN-14 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

gtin8.desc: The [GTIN-8](http://apps.gs1.org/GDD/glossary/Pages/GTIN-8.aspx) code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This code is also known as EAN/UCC-8 or 8-digit EAN. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

includesObject.desc: This links to a node or nodes indicating the exact quantity of the products included in the offer.

ineligibleRegion.desc: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is not valid, e.g. a region where the transaction is not allowed.\n\nSee also [[eligibleRegion]].

inventoryLevel.desc: The current approximate inventory level for the item or items.

itemCondition.desc: A predefined value from OfferItemCondition or a textual description of the condition of the product or service, or the products or services included in the offer.

mpn.desc: The Manufacturer Part Number (MPN) of the product, or the product to which the offer refers.

priceSpecification.desc: One or more detailed price specifications, indicating the unit price and delivery or payment charges.

seller.desc: An entity which offers (sells / leases / lends / loans) the services / goods.  A seller may also be a provider.

serialNumber.desc: The serial number or any alphanumeric identifier of a particular product. When attached to an offer, it is a shortcut for the serial number of the product included in the offer.

sku.desc: The Stock Keeping Unit (SKU), i.e. a merchant-specific identifier for a product or service, or the product to which the offer refers.

validFrom.desc: The date when the item becomes valid.

validThrough.desc: The date after when the item is not valid. For example the end of an offer, salary period, or a period of opening hours.

warranty.desc: The warranty promise(s) included in the offer.

http://schema.org/DepartAction.desc: The act of  departing from a place. An agent departs from an fromLocation for a destination, optionally with participants.

http://schema.org/DepositAccount.desc: A type of Bank Account with a main purpose of depositing funds to gain interest or other benefits.

hasDigitalDocumentPermission.desc: A permission related to the access to this document (e.g. permission to read or write an electronic document). For a public document, specify a grantee with an Audience with audienceType equal to "public".

http://schema.org/DigitalDocumentPermiss.desc: A permission for a particular person or group to access a particular file.

grantee.desc: The person, organization, contact point, or audience that has been granted this permission.

permissionType.desc: The type of permission granted the person, organization, or audience.

http://schema.org/DigitalDocumentPermiss.desc: A type of permission which can be granted for accessing a digital document.

http://schema.org/DisagreeAction.desc: The act of expressing a difference of opinion with the object. An agent disagrees to/about an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.

http://schema.org/DiscoverAction.desc: The act of discovering/finding an object.

http://schema.org/DiscussionForumPosting.desc: A posting to a discussion forum.

http://schema.org/DislikeAction.desc: The act of expressing a negative sentiment about the object. An agent dislikes an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.

http://schema.org/Distance.desc: Properties that take Distances as values are of the form '<Number> <Length unit of measure>'. E.g., '7 ft'.

http://schema.org/DonateAction.desc: The act of providing goods, services, or money without compensation, often for philanthropic reasons.

recipient.desc: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

http://schema.org/DownloadAction.desc: The act of downloading an object.

http://schema.org/DrawAction.desc: The act of producing a visual/graphical representation of an object, typically with a pen/pencil and paper as instruments.

http://schema.org/DriveWheelConfiguratio.desc: A value indicating which roadwheels will receive torque.

http://schema.org/EatAction.desc: The act of swallowing solid objects.

http://schema.org/EmergencyService.desc: An emergency service, such as a fire station or ER.

http://schema.org/EmployeeRole.desc: A subclass of OrganizationRole used to describe employee relationships.

baseSalary.desc: The base salary of the job or of an employee in an EmployeeRole.

salaryCurrency.desc: The currency (coded using [ISO 4217](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) ) used for the main salary information in this job posting or for this employee.

http://schema.org/EmployerAggregateRatin.desc: An aggregate rating of an Organization related to its role as an employer.

endorsee.desc: A sub property of participant. The person/organization being supported.

http://schema.org/EndorsementRating.desc:
An EndorsementRating is a rating that expresses some level of endorsement, for example inclusion in a "critic's pick" blog, a
"Like" or "+1" on a social network. It can be considered the [[result]] of an [[EndorseAction]] in which the [[object]] of the action is rated positively by
some [[agent]]. As is common elsewhere in schema.org, it is sometimes more useful to describe the results of such an action without explicitly describing the [[Action]].

An [[EndorsementRating]] may be part of a numeric scale or organized system, but this is not required: having an explicit type for indicating a positive,
endorsement rating is particularly useful in the absence of numeric scales as it helps consumers understand that the rating is broadly positive.

http://schema.org/Energy.desc: Properties that take Energy as values are of the form '<Number> <Energy unit of measure>'.

http://schema.org/EngineSpecification.desc: Information about the engine of the vehicle. A vehicle can have multiple engines represented by multiple engine specification entities.

fuelType.desc: The type of fuel suitable for the engine or engines of the vehicle. If the vehicle has only one engine, this property can be attached directly to the vehicle.

http://schema.org/EntryPoint.desc: An entry point, within some Web-based protocol.

actionApplication.desc: An application that can complete the request.

actionPlatform.desc: The high level platform(s) where the Action can be performed for the given URL. To specify a specific application or operating system instance, use actionApplication.

application.desc: An application that can complete the request.

contentType.desc: The supported content type(s) for an EntryPoint response.

encodingType.desc: The supported encoding type(s) for an EntryPoint request.

httpMethod.desc: An HTTP method that specifies the appropriate HTTP method for a request to an HTTP EntryPoint. Values are capitalized strings as used in HTTP.

urlTemplate.desc: An url template (RFC6570) that will be used to construct the target of the execution of the action.

http://schema.org/Enumeration.desc: Lists or enumerationsfor example, a list of cuisines or music genres, etc.

http://schema.org/Episode.desc: A media episode (e.g. TV, radio, video game) which can be part of a series or season.

actor.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

actors.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

director.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

directors.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

episodeNumber.desc: Position of the episode within an ordered group of episodes.

partOfSeason.desc: The season to which this episode belongs.

partOfSeries.desc: The series to which this episode or season belongs.

productionCompany.desc: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

trailer.desc: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

http://schema.org/Event.desc: An event happening at a certain time and location, such as a concert, lecture, or festival. Ticketing information may be added via the [[offers]] property. Repeated events may be structured as separate Event objects.

about.desc: The subject matter of the content.

actor.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

aggregateRating.desc: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

attendee.desc: A person or organization attending the event.

audience.desc: An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.

composer.desc: The person or organization who wrote a composition, or who is the composer of a work performed at some event.

contributor.desc: A secondary contributor to the CreativeWork or Event.

director.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

duration.desc: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

endDate.desc: The end date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

eventStatus.desc: An eventStatus of an event represents its status; particularly useful when an event is cancelled or rescheduled.

funder.desc: A person or organization that supports (sponsors) something through some kind of financial contribution.

inLanguage.desc: The language of the content or performance or used in an action. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[availableLanguage]].

isAccessibleForFree.desc: A flag to signal that the item, event, or place is accessible for free.

location.desc: The location of for example where the event is happening, an organization is located, or where an action takes place.

maximumAttendeeCapacity.desc: The total number of individuals that may attend an event or venue.

offers.desc: An offer to provide this itemfor example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event.

performer.desc: A performer at the eventfor example, a presenter, musician, musical group or actor.

performers.desc: The main performer or performers of the eventfor example, a presenter, musician, or actor.

previousStartDate.desc: Used in conjunction with eventStatus for rescheduled or cancelled events. This property contains the previously scheduled start date. For rescheduled events, the startDate property should be used for the newly scheduled start date. In the (rare) case of an event that has been postponed and rescheduled multiple times, this field may be repeated.

recordedIn.desc: The CreativeWork that captured all or part of this Event.

remainingAttendeeCapacity.desc: The number of attendee places for an event that remain unallocated.

sponsor.desc: A person or organization that supports a thing through a pledge, promise, or financial contribution. e.g. a sponsor of a Medical Study or a corporate sponsor of an event.

startDate.desc: The start date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

subEvent.desc: An Event that is part of this event. For example, a conference event includes many presentations, each of which is a subEvent of the conference.

subEvents.desc: Events that are a part of this event. For example, a conference event includes many presentations, each subEvents of the conference.

superEvent.desc: An event that this event is a part of. For example, a collection of individual music performances might each have a music festival as their superEvent.

translator.desc: Organization or person who adapts a creative work to different languages, regional differences and technical requirements of a target market, or that translates during some event.
