typicalAgeRange.desc: The typical expected age range, e.g. '7-9', '11-'.

workFeatured.desc:
A work featured in some event, e.g. exhibited in an ExhibitionEvent.
       Specific subproperties are available for workPerformed (e.g. a play), or a workPresented (a Movie at a ScreeningEvent).

workPerformed.desc: A work performed in some event, for example a play performed in a TheaterEvent.

http://schema.org/EventReservation.desc: A reservation for an event like a concert, sporting event, or lecture.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, use [[Offer]].

http://schema.org/EventStatusType.desc: EventStatusType is an enumeration type whose instances represent several states that an Event may be in.

http://schema.org/ExerciseAction.desc: The act of participating in exertive activity for the purposes of improving health and fitness.

course.desc: A sub property of location. The course where this action was taken.

distance.desc: The distance travelled, e.g. exercising or travelling.

exerciseCourse.desc: A sub property of location. The course where this action was taken.

fromLocation.desc: A sub property of location. The original location of the object or the agent before the action.

opponent.desc: A sub property of participant. The opponent on this action.

sportsActivityLocation.desc: A sub property of location. The sports activity location where this action occurred.

sportsEvent.desc: A sub property of location. The sports event where this action occurred.

sportsTeam.desc: A sub property of participant. The sports team that participated on this action.

toLocation.desc: A sub property of location. The final location of the object or the agent after the action.

http://schema.org/ExhibitionEvent.desc: Event type: Exhibition event, e.g. at a museum, library, archive, tradeshow, ...

http://schema.org/FAQPage.desc: A [[FAQPage]] is a [[WebPage]] presenting one or more "[Frequently asked questions](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FAQ)" (see also [[QAPage]]).

http://schema.org/FMRadioChannel.desc: A radio channel that uses FM.

http://schema.org/FilmAction.desc: The act of capturing sound and moving images on film, video, or digitally.

http://schema.org/FinancialProduct.desc: A product provided to consumers and businesses by financial institutions such as banks, insurance companies, brokerage firms, consumer finance companies, and investment companies which comprise the financial services industry.

annualPercentageRate.desc: The annual rate that is charged for borrowing (or made by investing), expressed as a single percentage number that represents the actual yearly cost of funds over the term of a loan. This includes any fees or additional costs associated with the transaction.

feesAndCommissionsSpecification.desc: Description of fees, commissions, and other terms applied either to a class of financial product, or by a financial service organization.

interestRate.desc: The interest rate, charged or paid, applicable to the financial product. Note: This is different from the calculated annualPercentageRate.

feesAndCommissionsSpecification.desc: Description of fees, commissions, and other terms applied either to a class of financial product, or by a financial service organization.

http://schema.org/FindAction.desc:
The act of finding an object.

Related actions:

* [[SearchAction]]: FindAction is generally lead by a SearchAction, but not necessarily.

arrivalAirport.desc: The airport where the flight terminates.

arrivalGate.desc: Identifier of the flight's arrival gate.

arrivalTerminal.desc: Identifier of the flight's arrival terminal.

boardingPolicy.desc: The type of boarding policy used by the airline (e.g. zone-based or group-based).

carrier.desc: 'carrier' is an out-dated term indicating the 'provider' for parcel delivery and flights.

departureAirport.desc: The airport where the flight originates.

departureGate.desc: Identifier of the flight's departure gate.

departureTerminal.desc: Identifier of the flight's departure terminal.

estimatedFlightDuration.desc: The estimated time the flight will take.

flightNumber.desc: The unique identifier for a flight including the airline IATA code. For example, if describing United flight 110, where the IATA code for United is 'UA', the flightNumber is 'UA110'.

mealService.desc: Description of the meals that will be provided or available for purchase.

seller.desc: An entity which offers (sells / leases / lends / loans) the services / goods.  A seller may also be a provider.

webCheckinTime.desc: The time when a passenger can check into the flight online.

http://schema.org/FlightReservation.desc: A reservation for air travel.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, use [[Offer]].

boardingGroup.desc: The airline-specific indicator of boarding order / preference.

passengerPriorityStatus.desc: The priority status assigned to a passenger for security or boarding (e.g. FastTrack or Priority).

passengerSequenceNumber.desc: The passenger's sequence number as assigned by the airline.

securityScreening.desc: The type of security screening the passenger is subject to.

http://schema.org/FollowAction.desc:
The act of forming a personal connection with someone/something (object) unidirectionally/asymmetrically to get updates polled from.

Related actions:

* [[BefriendAction]]: Unlike BefriendAction, FollowAction implies that the connection is *not* necessarily reciprocal.
* [[SubscribeAction]]: Unlike SubscribeAction, FollowAction implies that the follower acts as an active agent constantly/actively polling for updates.
* [[RegisterAction]]: Unlike RegisterAction, FollowAction implies that the agent is interested in continuing receiving updates from the object.
* [[JoinAction]]: Unlike JoinAction, FollowAction implies that the agent is interested in getting updates from the object.
* [[TrackAction]]: Unlike TrackAction, FollowAction refers to the polling of updates of all aspects of animate objects rather than the location of inanimate objects (e.g. you track a package, but you don't follow it).

followee.desc: A sub property of object. The person or organization being followed.

acceptsReservations.desc: Indicates whether a FoodEstablishment accepts reservations. Values can be Boolean, an URL at which reservations can be made or (for backwards compatibility) the strings ```Yes``` or ```No```.

hasMenu.desc: Either the actual menu as a structured representation, as text, or a URL of the menu.

menu.desc: Either the actual menu as a structured representation, as text, or a URL of the menu.

starRating.desc: An official rating for a lodging business or food establishment, e.g. from national associations or standards bodies. Use the author property to indicate the rating organization, e.g. as an Organization with name such as (e.g. HOTREC, DEHOGA, WHR, or Hotelstars).

http://schema.org/FoodEstablishmentReser.desc: A reservation to dine at a food-related business.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations.

endTime.desc: The endTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to end. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from January to *December*. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the end of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

partySize.desc: Number of people the reservation should accommodate.

startTime.desc: The startTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to start. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from *January* to December. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the start of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

http://schema.org/FoodService.desc: A food service, like breakfast, lunch, or dinner.

http://schema.org/Game.desc: The Game type represents things which are games. These are typically rule-governed recreational activities, e.g. role-playing games in which players assume the role of characters in a fictional setting.

characterAttribute.desc: A piece of data that represents a particular aspect of a fictional character (skill, power, character points, advantage, disadvantage).

gameItem.desc: An item is an object within the game world that can be collected by a player or, occasionally, a non-player character.

gameLocation.desc: Real or fictional location of the game (or part of game).

numberOfPlayers.desc: Indicate how many people can play this game (minimum, maximum, or range).

quest.desc: The task that a player-controlled character, or group of characters may complete in order to gain a reward.

http://schema.org/GamePlayMode.desc: Indicates whether this game is multi-player, co-op or single-player.

http://schema.org/GameServer.desc: Server that provides game interaction in a multiplayer game.

game.desc: Video game which is played on this server.

playersOnline.desc: Number of players on the server.

http://schema.org/GeoCircle.desc:
A GeoCircle is a GeoShape representing a circular geographic area. As it is a GeoShape
          it provides the simple textual property 'circle', but also allows the combination of postalCode alongside geoRadius.
          The center of the circle can be indicated via the 'geoMidpoint' property, or more approximately using 'address', 'postalCode'.

geoMidpoint.desc: Indicates the GeoCoordinates at the centre of a GeoShape e.g. GeoCircle.

geoRadius.desc: Indicates the approximate radius of a GeoCircle (metres unless indicated otherwise via Distance notation).

http://schema.org/GeoCoordinates.desc: The geographic coordinates of a place or event.

addressCountry.desc: The country. For example, USA. You can also provide the two-letter [ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166-1).

elevation.desc: The elevation of a location ([WGS 84](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Geodetic_System)). Values may be of the form 'NUMBER UNIT_OF_MEASUREMENT' (e.g., '1,000 m', '3,200 ft') while numbers alone should be assumed to be a value in meters.

latitude.desc: The latitude of a location. For example ```37.42242``` ([WGS 84](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Geodetic_System)).

longitude.desc: The longitude of a location. For example ```-122.08585``` ([WGS 84](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Geodetic_System)).

http://schema.org/GeoShape.desc: The geographic shape of a place. A GeoShape can be described using several properties whose values are based on latitude/longitude pairs. Either whitespace or commas can be used to separate latitude and longitude; whitespace should be used when writing a list of several such points.

addressCountry.desc: The country. For example, USA. You can also provide the two-letter [ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166-1).

box.desc: A box is the area enclosed by the rectangle formed by two points. The first point is the lower corner, the second point is the upper corner. A box is expressed as two points separated by a space character.

circle.desc: A circle is the circular region of a specified radius centered at a specified latitude and longitude. A circle is expressed as a pair followed by a radius in meters.

elevation.desc: The elevation of a location ([WGS 84](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Geodetic_System)). Values may be of the form 'NUMBER UNIT_OF_MEASUREMENT' (e.g., '1,000 m', '3,200 ft') while numbers alone should be assumed to be a value in meters.

line.desc: A line is a point-to-point path consisting of two or more points. A line is expressed as a series of two or more point objects separated by space.

polygon.desc: A polygon is the area enclosed by a point-to-point path for which the starting and ending points are the same. A polygon is expressed as a series of four or more space delimited points where the first and final points are identical.

http://schema.org/GiveAction.desc:
The act of transferring ownership of an object to a destination. Reciprocal of TakeAction.

Related actions:

* [[TakeAction]]: Reciprocal of GiveAction.
* [[SendAction]]: Unlike SendAction, GiveAction implies that ownership is being transferred (e.g. I may send my laptop to you, but that doesn't mean I'm giving it to you).

recipient.desc: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

http://schema.org/GovernmentOffice.desc: A government officefor example, an IRS or DMV office.

http://schema.org/GovernmentPermit.desc: A permit issued by a government agency.

http://schema.org/GovernmentService.desc: A service provided by a government organization, e.g. food stamps, veterans benefits, etc.

serviceOperator.desc: The operating organization, if different from the provider.  This enables the representation of services that are provided by an organization, but operated by another organization like a subcontractor.

http://schema.org/HVACBusiness.desc: A business that provide Heating, Ventilation and Air Conditioning services.

http://schema.org/HobbyShop.desc: A store that sells materials useful or necessary for various hobbies.

http://schema.org/HomeAndConstructionBus.desc:
A construction business.

A HomeAndConstructionBusiness is a [[LocalBusiness]] that provides services around homes and buildings.

As a [[LocalBusiness]] it can be described as a [[provider]] of one or more [[Service]]\(s).

http://schema.org/Hostel.desc:
A hostel - cheap accommodation, often in shared dormitories.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

http://schema.org/Hotel.desc:
A hotel is an establishment that provides lodging paid on a short-term basis (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hotel).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

http://schema.org/HotelRoom.desc:
A hotel room is a single room in a hotel.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

bed.desc:
The type of bed or beds included in the accommodation. For the single case of just one bed of a certain type, you use bed directly with a text.
      If you want to indicate the quantity of a certain kind of bed, use an instance of BedDetails. For more detailed information, use the amenityFeature property.

occupancy.desc:
The allowed total occupancy for the accommodation in persons (including infants etc). For individual accommodations, this is not necessarily the legal maximum but defines the permitted usage as per the contractual agreement (e.g. a double room used by a single person).
Typical unit code(s): C62 for person

http://schema.org/House.desc: A house is a building or structure that has the ability to be occupied for habitation by humans or other creatures (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/House).

numberOfRooms.desc:
The number of rooms (excluding bathrooms and closets) of the accommodation or lodging business.
Typical unit code(s): ROM for room or C62 for no unit. The type of room can be put in the unitText property of the QuantitativeValue.

http://schema.org/HowTo.desc: Instructions that explain how to achieve a result by performing a sequence of steps.

estimatedCost.desc: The estimated cost of the supply or supplies consumed when performing instructions.

performTime.desc: The length of time it takes to perform instructions or a direction (not including time to prepare the supplies), in [ISO 8601 duration format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

prepTime.desc: The length of time it takes to prepare the items to be used in instructions or a direction, in [ISO 8601 duration format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

step.desc: A single step item (as HowToStep, text, document, video, etc.) or a HowToSection.

steps.desc: A single step item (as HowToStep, text, document, video, etc.) or a HowToSection (originally misnamed 'steps'; 'step' is preferred).

supply.desc: A sub-property of instrument. A supply consumed when performing instructions or a direction.

tool.desc: A sub property of instrument. An object used (but not consumed) when performing instructions or a direction.

totalTime.desc: The total time required to perform instructions or a direction (including time to prepare the supplies), in [ISO 8601 duration format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

yield.desc: The quantity that results by performing instructions. For example, a paper airplane, 10 personalized candles.

http://schema.org/HowToDirection.desc: A direction indicating a single action to do in the instructions for how to achieve a result.

afterMedia.desc: A media object representing the circumstances after performing this direction.

beforeMedia.desc: A media object representing the circumstances before performing this direction.

duringMedia.desc: A media object representing the circumstances while performing this direction.

performTime.desc: The length of time it takes to perform instructions or a direction (not including time to prepare the supplies), in [ISO 8601 duration format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

prepTime.desc: The length of time it takes to prepare the items to be used in instructions or a direction, in [ISO 8601 duration format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

supply.desc: A sub-property of instrument. A supply consumed when performing instructions or a direction.

tool.desc: A sub property of instrument. An object used (but not consumed) when performing instructions or a direction.

totalTime.desc: The total time required to perform instructions or a direction (including time to prepare the supplies), in [ISO 8601 duration format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

http://schema.org/HowToItem.desc: An item used as either a tool or supply when performing the instructions for how to to achieve a result.

requiredQuantity.desc: The required quantity of the item(s).

http://schema.org/HowToSection.desc: A sub-grouping of steps in the instructions for how to achieve a result (e.g. steps for making a pie crust within a pie recipe).

steps.desc: A single step item (as HowToStep, text, document, video, etc.) or a HowToSection (originally misnamed 'steps'; 'step' is preferred).

http://schema.org/HowToStep.desc: A step in the instructions for how to achieve a result. It is an ordered list with HowToDirection and/or HowToTip items.

http://schema.org/HowToSupply.desc: A supply consumed when performing the instructions for how to achieve a result.

estimatedCost.desc: The estimated cost of the supply or supplies consumed when performing instructions.

http://schema.org/HowToTip.desc: An explanation in the instructions for how to achieve a result. It provides supplementary information about a technique, supply, author's preference, etc. It can explain what could be done, or what should not be done, but doesn't specify what should be done (see HowToDirection).

http://schema.org/HowToTool.desc: A tool used (but not consumed) when performing instructions for how to achieve a result.

http://schema.org/IgnoreAction.desc: The act of intentionally disregarding the object. An agent ignores an object.

http://schema.org/ImageGallery.desc: Web page type: Image gallery page.

caption.desc: The caption for this object. For downloadable machine formats (closed caption, subtitles etc.) use MediaObject and indicate the [[encodingFormat]].

representativeOfPage.desc: Indicates whether this image is representative of the content of the page.

thumbnail.desc: Thumbnail image for an image or video.

http://schema.org/IndividualProduct.desc: A single, identifiable product instance (e.g. a laptop with a particular serial number).

serialNumber.desc: The serial number or any alphanumeric identifier of a particular product. When attached to an offer, it is a shortcut for the serial number of the product included in the offer.

http://schema.org/InformAction.desc: The act of notifying someone of information pertinent to them, with no expectation of a response.

event.desc: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

http://schema.org/InsertAction.desc: The act of adding at a specific location in an ordered collection.

toLocation.desc: A sub property of location. The final location of the object or the agent after the action.

http://schema.org/InstallAction.desc: The act of installing an application.

http://schema.org/Intangible.desc: A utility class that serves as the umbrella for a number of 'intangible' things such as quantities, structured values, etc.

http://schema.org/InteractAction.desc: The act of interacting with another person or organization.

http://schema.org/InteractionCounter.desc: A summary of how users have interacted with this CreativeWork. In most cases, authors will use a subtype to specify the specific type of interaction.

interactionService.desc: The WebSite or SoftwareApplication where the interactions took place.

interactionType.desc: The Action representing the type of interaction. For up votes, +1s, etc. use [[LikeAction]]. For down votes use [[DislikeAction]]. Otherwise, use the most specific Action.

userInteractionCount.desc: The number of interactions for the CreativeWork using the WebSite or SoftwareApplication.

http://schema.org/InvestmentOrDeposit.desc: A type of financial product that typically requires the client to transfer funds to a financial service in return for potential beneficial financial return.

http://schema.org/InviteAction.desc: The act of asking someone to attend an event. Reciprocal of RsvpAction.

event.desc: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

http://schema.org/Invoice.desc: A statement of the money due for goods or services; a bill.

accountId.desc: The identifier for the account the payment will be applied to.

billingPeriod.desc: The time interval used to compute the invoice.

broker.desc: An entity that arranges for an exchange between a buyer and a seller.  In most cases a broker never acquires or releases ownership of a product or service involved in an exchange.  If it is not clear whether an entity is a broker, seller, or buyer, the latter two terms are preferred.

category.desc: A category for the item. Greater signs or slashes can be used to informally indicate a category hierarchy.

confirmationNumber.desc: A number that confirms the given order or payment has been received.

customer.desc: Party placing the order or paying the invoice.

minimumPaymentDue.desc: The minimum payment required at this time.

paymentDue.desc: The date that payment is due.

paymentDueDate.desc: The date that payment is due.

paymentMethod.desc: The name of the credit card or other method of payment for the order.

paymentMethodId.desc: An identifier for the method of payment used (e.g. the last 4 digits of the credit card).

paymentStatus.desc: The status of payment; whether the invoice has been paid or not.

provider.desc: The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.

referencesOrder.desc: The Order(s) related to this Invoice. One or more Orders may be combined into a single Invoice.

scheduledPaymentDate.desc: The date the invoice is scheduled to be paid.

http://schema.org/ItemAvailability.desc: A list of possible product availability options.

http://schema.org/ItemList.desc: A list of items of any sortfor example, Top 10 Movies About Weathermen, or Top 100 Party Songs. Not to be confused with HTML lists, which are often used only for formatting.

itemListElement.desc:
For itemListElement values, you can use simple strings (e.g. "Peter", "Paul", "Mary"), existing entities, or use ListItem.

Text values are best if the elements in the list are plain strings. Existing entities are best for a simple, unordered list of existing things in your data. ListItem is used with ordered lists when you want to provide additional context about the element in that list or when the same item might be in different places in different lists.

Note: The order of elements in your mark-up is not sufficient for indicating the order or elements.  Use ListItem with a 'position' property in such cases.

itemListOrder.desc: Type of ordering (e.g. Ascending, Descending, Unordered).

numberOfItems.desc: The number of items in an ItemList. Note that some descriptions might not fully describe all items in a list (e.g., multi-page pagination); in such cases, the numberOfItems would be for the entire list.

http://schema.org/ItemListOrderType.desc: Enumerated for values for itemListOrder for indicating how an ordered ItemList is organized.

http://schema.org/ItemPage.desc: A page devoted to a single item, such as a particular product or hotel.

http://schema.org/JobPosting.desc: A listing that describes a job opening in a certain organization.

baseSalary.desc: The base salary of the job or of an employee in an EmployeeRole.

benefits.desc: Description of benefits associated with the job.

datePosted.desc: Publication date for the job posting.

educationRequirements.desc: Educational background needed for the position or Occupation.

employmentType.desc: Type of employment (e.g. full-time, part-time, contract, temporary, seasonal, internship).

estimatedSalary.desc: An estimated salary for a job posting or occupation, based on a variety of variables including, but not limited to industry, job title, and location. Estimated salaries  are often computed by outside organizations rather than the hiring organization, who may not have committed to the estimated value.

experienceRequirements.desc: Description of skills and experience needed for the position or Occupation.

incentiveCompensation.desc: Description of bonus and commission compensation aspects of the job.

incentives.desc: Description of bonus and commission compensation aspects of the job.

industry.desc: The industry associated with the job position.

jobBenefits.desc: Description of benefits associated with the job.

jobLocation.desc: A (typically single) geographic location associated with the job position.

occupationalCategory.desc: Category or categories describing the job. Use BLS O*NET-SOC taxonomy: http://www.onetcenter.org/taxonomy.html. Ideally includes textual label and formal code, with the property repeated for each applicable value.

qualifications.desc: Specific qualifications required for this role or Occupation.

responsibilities.desc: Responsibilities associated with this role or Occupation.

salaryCurrency.desc: The currency (coded using [ISO 4217](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) ) used for the main salary information in this job posting or for this employee.

skills.desc: Skills required to fulfill this role or in this Occupation.

specialCommitments.desc: Any special commitments associated with this job posting. Valid entries include VeteranCommit, MilitarySpouseCommit, etc.

validThrough.desc: The date after when the item is not valid. For example the end of an offer, salary period, or a period of opening hours.

workHours.desc: The typical working hours for this job (e.g. 1st shift, night shift, 8am-5pm).

http://schema.org/JoinAction.desc:
An agent joins an event/group with participants/friends at a location.

Related actions:

* [[RegisterAction]]: Unlike RegisterAction, JoinAction refers to joining a group/team of people.
* [[SubscribeAction]]: Unlike SubscribeAction, JoinAction does not imply that you'll be receiving updates.
* [[FollowAction]]: Unlike FollowAction, JoinAction does not imply that you'll be polling for updates.

event.desc: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

http://schema.org/Landform.desc: A landform or physical feature.  Landform elements include mountains, plains, lakes, rivers, seascape and oceanic waterbody interface features such as bays, peninsulas, seas and so forth, including sub-aqueous terrain features such as submersed mountain ranges, volcanoes, and the great ocean basins.

http://schema.org/Language.desc: Natural languages such as Spanish, Tamil, Hindi, English, etc. Formal language code tags expressed in [BCP 47](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IETF_language_tag) can be used via the [[alternateName]] property. The Language type previously also covered programming languages such as Scheme and Lisp, which are now best represented using [[ComputerLanguage]].

http://schema.org/LeaveAction.desc:
An agent leaves an event / group with participants/friends at a location.

Related actions:

* [[JoinAction]]: The antonym of LeaveAction.
* [[UnRegisterAction]]: Unlike UnRegisterAction, LeaveAction implies leaving a group/team of people rather than a service.

event.desc: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

http://schema.org/LegalService.desc: A LegalService is a business that provides legally-oriented services, advice and representation, e.g. law firms.\n\nAs a [[LocalBusiness]] it can be described as a [[provider]] of one or more [[Service]]\(s).

http://schema.org/LegislativeBuilding.desc: A legislative buildingfor example, the state capitol.

http://schema.org/LendAction.desc:
The act of providing an object under an agreement that it will be returned at a later date. Reciprocal of BorrowAction.

Related actions:

* [[BorrowAction]]: Reciprocal of LendAction.

borrower.desc: A sub property of participant. The person that borrows the object being lent.

http://schema.org/LikeAction.desc: The act of expressing a positive sentiment about the object. An agent likes an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.

http://schema.org/LiquorStore.desc: A shop that sells alcoholic drinks such as wine, beer, whisky and other spirits.

http://schema.org/ListItem.desc: An list item, e.g. a step in a checklist or how-to description.

item.desc: An entity represented by an entry in a list or data feed (e.g. an 'artist' in a list of 'artists').

nextItem.desc: A link to the ListItem that follows the current one.

position.desc: The position of an item in a series or sequence of items.

previousItem.desc: A link to the ListItem that preceeds the current one.

http://schema.org/ListenAction.desc: The act of consuming audio content.

http://schema.org/LiveBlogPosting.desc: A blog post intended to provide a rolling textual coverage of an ongoing event through continuous updates.

coverageEndTime.desc: The time when the live blog will stop covering the Event. Note that coverage may continue after the Event concludes.

coverageStartTime.desc: The time when the live blog will begin covering the Event. Note that coverage may begin before the Event's start time. The LiveBlogPosting may also be created before coverage begins.

http://schema.org/LoanOrCredit.desc: A financial product for the loaning of an amount of money under agreed terms and charges.

loanTerm.desc: The duration of the loan or credit agreement.

requiredCollateral.desc: Assets required to secure loan or credit repayments. It may take form of third party pledge, goods, financial instruments (cash, securities, etc.)

http://schema.org/LocalBusiness.desc: A particular physical business or branch of an organization. Examples of LocalBusiness include a restaurant, a particular branch of a restaurant chain, a branch of a bank, a medical practice, a club, a bowling alley, etc.

branchOf.desc: The larger organization that this local business is a branch of, if any. Not to be confused with (anatomical)[[branch]].

currenciesAccepted.desc: The currency accepted.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

openingHours.desc:
The general opening hours for a business. Opening hours can be specified as a weekly time range, starting with days, then times per day. Multiple days can be listed with commas ',' separating each day. Day or time ranges are specified using a hyphen '-'.

* Days are specified using the following two-letter combinations: ```Mo```, ```Tu```, ```We```, ```Th```, ```Fr```, ```Sa```, ```Su```.
* Times are specified using 24:00 time. For example, 3pm is specified as ```15:00```. 
* Here is an example: <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Tu,Th 16:00-20:00">Tuesdays and Thursdays 4-8pm</time>.
* If a business is open 7 days a week, then it can be specified as <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Mo-Su">Monday through Sunday, all day</time>.

paymentAccepted.desc: Cash, Credit Card, Cryptocurrency, Local Exchange Tradings System, etc.

priceRange.desc: The price range of the business, for example ```$$$```.

http://schema.org/LocationFeatureSpecifi.desc: Specifies a location feature by providing a structured value representing a feature of an accommodation as a property-value pair of varying degrees of formality.

hoursAvailable.desc: The hours during which this service or contact is available.

validFrom.desc: The date when the item becomes valid.

validThrough.desc: The date after when the item is not valid. For example the end of an offer, salary period, or a period of opening hours.

http://schema.org/LockerDelivery.desc: A DeliveryMethod in which an item is made available via locker.

http://schema.org/LodgingBusiness.desc: A lodging business, such as a motel, hotel, or inn.

amenityFeature.desc: An amenity feature (e.g. a characteristic or service) of the Accommodation. This generic property does not make a statement about whether the feature is included in an offer for the main accommodation or available at extra costs.

audience.desc: An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.

availableLanguage.desc: A language someone may use with or at the item, service or place. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[inLanguage]]

checkinTime.desc: The earliest someone may check into a lodging establishment.

checkoutTime.desc: The latest someone may check out of a lodging establishment.

numberOfRooms.desc:
The number of rooms (excluding bathrooms and closets) of the accommodation or lodging business.
Typical unit code(s): ROM for room or C62 for no unit. The type of room can be put in the unitText property of the QuantitativeValue.

petsAllowed.desc: Indicates whether pets are allowed to enter the accommodation or lodging business. More detailed information can be put in a text value.

starRating.desc: An official rating for a lodging business or food establishment, e.g. from national associations or standards bodies. Use the author property to indicate the rating organization, e.g. as an Organization with name such as (e.g. HOTREC, DEHOGA, WHR, or Hotelstars).

http://schema.org/LodgingReservation.desc: A reservation for lodging at a hotel, motel, inn, etc.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations.

checkinTime.desc: The earliest someone may check into a lodging establishment.

checkoutTime.desc: The latest someone may check out of a lodging establishment.

lodgingUnitDescription.desc: A full description of the lodging unit.

lodgingUnitType.desc: Textual description of the unit type (including suite vs. room, size of bed, etc.).

numAdults.desc: The number of adults staying in the unit.

numChildren.desc: The number of children staying in the unit.

http://schema.org/LoseAction.desc: The act of being defeated in a competitive activity.

winner.desc: A sub property of participant. The winner of the action.

mapType.desc: Indicates the kind of Map, from the MapCategoryType Enumeration.

http://schema.org/MapCategoryType.desc: An enumeration of several kinds of Map.

http://schema.org/MarryAction.desc: The act of marrying a person.

http://schema.org/Mass.desc: Properties that take Mass as values are of the form '<Number> <Mass unit of measure>'. E.g., '7 kg'.

http://schema.org/MediaObject.desc: A media object, such as an image, video, or audio object embedded in a web page or a downloadable dataset i.e. DataDownload. Note that a creative work may have many media objects associated with it on the same web page. For example, a page about a single song (MusicRecording) may have a music video (VideoObject), and a high and low bandwidth audio stream (2 AudioObject's).

associatedArticle.desc: A NewsArticle associated with the Media Object.

bitrate.desc: The bitrate of the media object.

contentUrl.desc: Actual bytes of the media object, for example the image file or video file.

duration.desc: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

embedUrl.desc: A URL pointing to a player for a specific video. In general, this is the information in the ```src``` element of an ```embed``` tag and should not be the same as the content of the ```loc``` tag.

encodesCreativeWork.desc: The CreativeWork encoded by this media object.

encodingFormat.desc:
Media type typically expressed using a MIME format (see [IANA site](http://www.iana.org/assignments/media-types/media-types.xhtml) and [MDN reference](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Basics_of_HTTP/MIME_types)) e.g. application/zip for a SoftwareApplication binary, audio/mpeg for .mp3 etc.).

In cases where a [[CreativeWork]] has several media type representations, [[encoding]] can be used to indicate each [[MediaObject]] alongside particular [[encodingFormat]] information.

Unregistered or niche encoding and file formats can be indicated instead via the most appropriate URL, e.g. defining Web page or a Wikipedia/Wikidata entry.

endTime.desc: The endTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to end. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from January to *December*. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the end of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

playerType.desc: Player type requiredfor example, Flash or Silverlight.

productionCompany.desc: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

regionsAllowed.desc: The regions where the media is allowed. If not specified, then it's assumed to be allowed everywhere. Specify the countries in [ISO 3166 format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166).

requiresSubscription.desc: Indicates if use of the media require a subscription  (either paid or free). Allowed values are ```true``` or ```false``` (note that an earlier version had 'yes', 'no').

startTime.desc: The startTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to start. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from *January* to December. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the start of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

uploadDate.desc: Date when this media object was uploaded to this site.

http://schema.org/MediaSubscription.desc: A subscription which allows a user to access media including audio, video, books, etc.

authenticator.desc: The Organization responsible for authenticating the user's subscription. For example, many media apps require a cable/satellite provider to authenticate your subscription before playing media.

expectsAcceptanceOf.desc: An Offer which must be accepted before the user can perform the Action. For example, the user may need to buy a movie before being able to watch it.

http://schema.org/MedicalOrganization.desc: A medical organization (physical or not), such as hospital, institution or clinic.

http://schema.org/MeetingRoom.desc:
A meeting room, conference room, or conference hall is a room provided for singular events such as business conferences and meetings (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conference_hall).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

http://schema.org/Menu.desc: A structured representation of food or drink items available from a FoodEstablishment.

hasMenuItem.desc: A food or drink item contained in a menu or menu section.

hasMenuSection.desc: A subgrouping of the menu (by dishes, course, serving time period, etc.).

http://schema.org/MenuItem.desc: A food or drink item listed in a menu or menu section.

menuAddOn.desc: Additional menu item(s) such as a side dish of salad or side order of fries that can be added to this menu item. Additionally it can be a menu section containing allowed add-on menu items for this menu item.

nutrition.desc: Nutrition information about the recipe or menu item.

offers.desc: An offer to provide this itemfor example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event.

suitableForDiet.desc: Indicates a dietary restriction or guideline for which this recipe or menu item is suitable, e.g. diabetic, halal etc.

http://schema.org/MenuSection.desc: A sub-grouping of food or drink items in a menu. E.g. courses (such as 'Dinner', 'Breakfast', etc.), specific type of dishes (such as 'Meat', 'Vegan', 'Drinks', etc.), or some other classification made by the menu provider.

hasMenuItem.desc: A food or drink item contained in a menu or menu section.

hasMenuSection.desc: A subgrouping of the menu (by dishes, course, serving time period, etc.).

http://schema.org/Message.desc: A single message from a sender to one or more organizations or people.

bccRecipient.desc: A sub property of recipient. The recipient blind copied on a message.

ccRecipient.desc: A sub property of recipient. The recipient copied on a message.

dateRead.desc: The date/time at which the message has been read by the recipient if a single recipient exists.

dateReceived.desc: The date/time the message was received if a single recipient exists.

dateSent.desc: The date/time at which the message was sent.

messageAttachment.desc: A CreativeWork attached to the message.

recipient.desc: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

sender.desc: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the sending end of the action.

toRecipient.desc: A sub property of recipient. The recipient who was directly sent the message.

http://schema.org/MiddleSchool.desc: A middle school (typically for children aged around 11-14, although this varies somewhat).

http://schema.org/MobileApplication.desc: A software application designed specifically to work well on a mobile device such as a telephone.

carrierRequirements.desc: Specifies specific carrier(s) requirements for the application (e.g. an application may only work on a specific carrier network).

http://schema.org/MobilePhoneStore.desc: A store that sells mobile phones and related accessories.

http://schema.org/MonetaryAmount.desc: A monetary value or range. This type can be used to describe an amount of money such as $50 USD, or a range as in describing a bank account being suitable for a balance between 1,000 and 1,000,000 GBP, or the value of a salary, etc. It is recommended to use [[PriceSpecification]] Types to describe the price of an Offer, Invoice, etc.

currency.desc: The currency in which the monetary amount is expressed.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

maxValue.desc: The upper value of some characteristic or property.

minValue.desc: The lower value of some characteristic or property.

validFrom.desc: The date when the item becomes valid.

validThrough.desc: The date after when the item is not valid. For example the end of an offer, salary period, or a period of opening hours.

value.desc:
The value of the quantitative value or property value node.

* For [[QuantitativeValue]] and [[MonetaryAmount]], the recommended type for values is 'Number'.
* For [[PropertyValue]], it can be 'Text;', 'Number', 'Boolean', or 'StructuredValue'.
* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.

http://schema.org/MonetaryAmountDistribu.desc: A statistical distribution of monetary amounts.

currency.desc: The currency in which the monetary amount is expressed.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

http://schema.org/Motel.desc:
A motel.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

http://schema.org/Mountain.desc: A mountain, like Mount Whitney or Mount Everest.

http://schema.org/MoveAction.desc:
The act of an agent relocating to a place.

Related actions:

* [[TransferAction]]: Unlike TransferAction, the subject of the move is a living Person or Organization rather than an inanimate object.

fromLocation.desc: A sub property of location. The original location of the object or the agent before the action.

toLocation.desc: A sub property of location. The final location of the object or the agent after the action.

actor.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

actors.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

countryOfOrigin.desc: The country of the principal offices of the production company or individual responsible for the movie or program.

director.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

directors.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

duration.desc: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

productionCompany.desc: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

subtitleLanguage.desc: Languages in which subtitles/captions are available, in [IETF BCP 47 standard format](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47).

trailer.desc: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

http://schema.org/MovieClip.desc: A short segment/part of a movie.

http://schema.org/MovieSeries.desc: A series of movies. Included movies can be indicated with the hasPart property.

actor.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

actors.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

director.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

directors.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

productionCompany.desc: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

trailer.desc: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

screenCount.desc: The number of screens in the movie theater.

albumProductionType.desc: Classification of the album by it's type of content: soundtrack, live album, studio album, etc.

albumReleaseType.desc: The kind of release which this album is: single, EP or album.

byArtist.desc: The artist that performed this album or recording.

http://schema.org/MusicAlbumProductionTy.desc: Classification of the album by it's type of content: soundtrack, live album, studio album, etc.

http://schema.org/MusicAlbumReleaseType.desc: The kind of release which this album is: single, EP or album.

composer.desc: The person or organization who wrote a composition, or who is the composer of a work performed at some event.

firstPerformance.desc: The date and place the work was first performed.

includedComposition.desc: Smaller compositions included in this work (e.g. a movement in a symphony).

iswcCode.desc: The International Standard Musical Work Code for the composition.

lyricist.desc: The person who wrote the words.

musicArrangement.desc: An arrangement derived from the composition.

musicCompositionForm.desc: The type of composition (e.g. overture, sonata, symphony, etc.).

musicalKey.desc: The key, mode, or scale this composition uses.

recordedAs.desc: An audio recording of the work.

http://schema.org/MusicGroup.desc: A musical group, such as a band, an orchestra, or a choir. Can also be a solo musician.

genre.desc: Genre of the creative work, broadcast channel or group.

musicGroupMember.desc: A member of a music groupfor example, John, Paul, George, or Ringo.

track.desc: A music recording (track)usually a single song. If an ItemList is given, the list should contain items of type MusicRecording.

tracks.desc: A music recording (track)usually a single song.

http://schema.org/MusicPlaylist.desc: A collection of music tracks in playlist form.

numTracks.desc: The number of tracks in this album or playlist.

track.desc: A music recording (track)usually a single song. If an ItemList is given, the list should contain items of type MusicRecording.

tracks.desc: A music recording (track)usually a single song.

http://schema.org/MusicRecording.desc: A music recording (track), usually a single song.

byArtist.desc: The artist that performed this album or recording.

duration.desc: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

inAlbum.desc: The album to which this recording belongs.

inPlaylist.desc: The playlist to which this recording belongs.

isrcCode.desc: The International Standard Recording Code for the recording.

recordingOf.desc: The composition this track is a recording of.

http://schema.org/MusicRelease.desc: A MusicRelease is a specific release of a music album.

catalogNumber.desc: The catalog number for the release.

creditedTo.desc: The group the release is credited to if different than the byArtist. For example, Red and Blue is credited to "Stefani Germanotta Band", but by Lady Gaga.

duration.desc: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

musicReleaseFormat.desc: Format of this release (the type of recording media used, ie. compact disc, digital media, LP, etc.).

recordLabel.desc: The label that issued the release.

releaseOf.desc: The album this is a release of.

http://schema.org/MusicReleaseFormatType.desc: Format of this release (the type of recording media used, ie. compact disc, digital media, LP, etc.).

http://schema.org/NewsArticle.desc:
A NewsArticle is an article whose content reports news, or provides background context and supporting materials for understanding the news.

A more detailed overview of [schema.org News markup](/docs/news.html) is also available.

dateline.desc:
A [dateline](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dateline) is a brief piece of text included in news articles that describes where and when the story was written or filed though the date is often omitted. Sometimes only a placename is provided.

Structured representations of dateline-related information can also be expressed more explicitly using [[locationCreated]] (which represents where a work was created e.g. where a news report was written).  For location depicted or described in the content, use [[contentLocation]].

Dateline summaries are oriented more towards human readers than towards automated processing, and can vary substantially. Some examples: "BEIRUT, Lebanon, June 2.", "Paris, France", "December 19, 2017 11:43AM Reporting from Washington", "Beijing/Moscow", "QUEZON CITY, Philippines".

printColumn.desc: The number of the column in which the NewsArticle appears in the print edition.

printEdition.desc: The edition of the print product in which the NewsArticle appears.

printPage.desc: If this NewsArticle appears in print, this field indicates the name of the page on which the article is found. Please note that this field is intended for the exact page name (e.g. A5, B18).

printSection.desc: If this NewsArticle appears in print, this field indicates the print section in which the article appeared.

http://schema.org/NoteDigitalDocument.desc: A file containing a note, primarily for the author.

carbohydrateContent.desc: The number of grams of carbohydrates.

cholesterolContent.desc: The number of milligrams of cholesterol.

fatContent.desc: The number of grams of fat.

fiberContent.desc: The number of grams of fiber.

proteinContent.desc: The number of grams of protein.

saturatedFatContent.desc: The number of grams of saturated fat.

servingSize.desc: The serving size, in terms of the number of volume or mass.

sodiumContent.desc: The number of milligrams of sodium.

sugarContent.desc: The number of grams of sugar.

transFatContent.desc: The number of grams of trans fat.

unsaturatedFatContent.desc: The number of grams of unsaturated fat.

http://schema.org/Occupation.desc: A profession, may involve prolonged training and/or a formal qualification.

educationRequirements.desc: Educational background needed for the position or Occupation.

estimatedSalary.desc: An estimated salary for a job posting or occupation, based on a variety of variables including, but not limited to industry, job title, and location. Estimated salaries  are often computed by outside organizations rather than the hiring organization, who may not have committed to the estimated value.

experienceRequirements.desc: Description of skills and experience needed for the position or Occupation.

occupationLocation.desc: The region/country for which this occupational description is appropriate. Note that educational requirements and qualifications can vary between jurisdictions.

occupationalCategory.desc: Category or categories describing the job. Use BLS O*NET-SOC taxonomy: http://www.onetcenter.org/taxonomy.html. Ideally includes textual label and formal code, with the property repeated for each applicable value.

qualifications.desc: Specific qualifications required for this role or Occupation.

responsibilities.desc: Responsibilities associated with this role or Occupation.

skills.desc: Skills required to fulfill this role or in this Occupation.

http://schema.org/Offer.desc: An offer to transfer some rights to an item or to provide a service  for example, an offer to sell tickets to an event, to rent the DVD of a movie, to stream a TV show over the internet, to repair a motorcycle, or to loan a book.\n\nFor [GTIN](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin)-related fields, see [Check Digit calculator](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/support/check_digit_calculator) and [validation guide](http://www.gs1us.org/resources/standards/gtin-validation-guide) from [GS1](http://www.gs1.org/).

acceptedPaymentMethod.desc: The payment method(s) accepted by seller for this offer.

addOn.desc: An additional offer that can only be obtained in combination with the first base offer (e.g. supplements and extensions that are available for a surcharge).

advanceBookingRequirement.desc: The amount of time that is required between accepting the offer and the actual usage of the resource or service.

aggregateRating.desc: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

areaServed.desc: The geographic area where a service or offered item is provided.

availability.desc: The availability of this itemfor example In stock, Out of stock, Pre-order, etc.

availabilityEnds.desc: The end of the availability of the product or service included in the offer.

availabilityStarts.desc: The beginning of the availability of the product or service included in the offer.

availableAtOrFrom.desc: The place(s) from which the offer can be obtained (e.g. store locations).

availableDeliveryMethod.desc: The delivery method(s) available for this offer.

businessFunction.desc: The business function (e.g. sell, lease, repair, dispose) of the offer or component of a bundle (TypeAndQuantityNode). The default is http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell.

category.desc: A category for the item. Greater signs or slashes can be used to informally indicate a category hierarchy.

deliveryLeadTime.desc: The typical delay between the receipt of the order and the goods either leaving the warehouse or being prepared for pickup, in case the delivery method is on site pickup.

eligibleCustomerType.desc: The type(s) of customers for which the given offer is valid.

eligibleDuration.desc: The duration for which the given offer is valid.

eligibleQuantity.desc: The interval and unit of measurement of ordering quantities for which the offer or price specification is valid. This allows e.g. specifying that a certain freight charge is valid only for a certain quantity.

eligibleRegion.desc: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is valid.\n\nSee also [[ineligibleRegion]].

eligibleTransactionVolume.desc: The transaction volume, in a monetary unit, for which the offer or price specification is valid, e.g. for indicating a minimal purchasing volume, to express free shipping above a certain order volume, or to limit the acceptance of credit cards to purchases to a certain minimal amount.

gtin12.desc: The GTIN-12 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. The GTIN-12 is the 12-digit GS1 Identification Key composed of a U.P.C. Company Prefix, Item Reference, and Check Digit used to identify trade items. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

gtin13.desc: The GTIN-13 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This is equivalent to 13-digit ISBN codes and EAN UCC-13. Former 12-digit UPC codes can be converted into a GTIN-13 code by simply adding a preceeding zero. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

gtin14.desc: The GTIN-14 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

gtin8.desc: The [GTIN-8](http://apps.gs1.org/GDD/glossary/Pages/GTIN-8.aspx) code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This code is also known as EAN/UCC-8 or 8-digit EAN. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

includesObject.desc: This links to a node or nodes indicating the exact quantity of the products included in the offer.

ineligibleRegion.desc: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is not valid, e.g. a region where the transaction is not allowed.\n\nSee also [[eligibleRegion]].

inventoryLevel.desc: The current approximate inventory level for the item or items.

itemCondition.desc: A predefined value from OfferItemCondition or a textual description of the condition of the product or service, or the products or services included in the offer.

mpn.desc: The Manufacturer Part Number (MPN) of the product, or the product to which the offer refers.

offeredBy.desc: A pointer to the organization or person making the offer.

price.desc:
The offer price of a product, or of a price component when attached to PriceSpecification and its subtypes.

Usage guidelines:

* Use the [[priceCurrency]] property (with standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR") instead of including [ambiguous symbols](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dollar_sign#Currencies_that_use_the_dollar_or_peso_sign) such as '$' in the value.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.
* Note that both [RDFa](http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-primer/#using-the-content-attribute) and Microdata syntax allow the use of a "content=" attribute for publishing simple machine-readable values alongside more human-friendly formatting.
* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.

priceCurrency.desc: The currency of the price, or a price component when attached to [[PriceSpecification]] and its subtypes.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

priceSpecification.desc: One or more detailed price specifications, indicating the unit price and delivery or payment charges.

priceValidUntil.desc: The date after which the price is no longer available.

seller.desc: An entity which offers (sells / leases / lends / loans) the services / goods.  A seller may also be a provider.

serialNumber.desc: The serial number or any alphanumeric identifier of a particular product. When attached to an offer, it is a shortcut for the serial number of the product included in the offer.

sku.desc: The Stock Keeping Unit (SKU), i.e. a merchant-specific identifier for a product or service, or the product to which the offer refers.

validFrom.desc: The date when the item becomes valid.

validThrough.desc: The date after when the item is not valid. For example the end of an offer, salary period, or a period of opening hours.

warranty.desc: The warranty promise(s) included in the offer.

http://schema.org/OfferCatalog.desc: An OfferCatalog is an ItemList that contains related Offers and/or further OfferCatalogs that are offeredBy the same provider.

http://schema.org/OfferItemCondition.desc: A list of possible conditions for the item.

http://schema.org/OnDemandEvent.desc: A publication event e.g. catch-up TV or radio podcast, during which a program is available on-demand.

http://schema.org/OpeningHoursSpecificat.desc:
A structured value providing information about the opening hours of a place or a certain service inside a place.


The place is __open__ if the [[opens]] property is specified, and __closed__ otherwise.

If the value for the [[closes]] property is less than the value for the [[opens]] property then the hour range is assumed to span over the next day.

closes.desc: The closing hour of the place or service on the given day(s) of the week.

dayOfWeek.desc: The day of the week for which these opening hours are valid.

opens.desc: The opening hour of the place or service on the given day(s) of the week.

validFrom.desc: The date when the item becomes valid.

validThrough.desc: The date after when the item is not valid. For example the end of an offer, salary period, or a period of opening hours.

http://schema.org/Order.desc: An order is a confirmation of a transaction (a receipt), which can contain multiple line items, each represented by an Offer that has been accepted by the customer.

acceptedOffer.desc: The offer(s) -- e.g., product, quantity and price combinations -- included in the order.

billingAddress.desc: The billing address for the order.

broker.desc: An entity that arranges for an exchange between a buyer and a seller.  In most cases a broker never acquires or releases ownership of a product or service involved in an exchange.  If it is not clear whether an entity is a broker, seller, or buyer, the latter two terms are preferred.

confirmationNumber.desc: A number that confirms the given order or payment has been received.

customer.desc: Party placing the order or paying the invoice.

discountCode.desc: Code used to redeem a discount.

discountCurrency.desc: The currency of the discount.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

isGift.desc: Was the offer accepted as a gift for someone other than the buyer.

orderDelivery.desc: The delivery of the parcel related to this order or order item.

orderStatus.desc: The current status of the order.

partOfInvoice.desc: The order is being paid as part of the referenced Invoice.

paymentDue.desc: The date that payment is due.

paymentDueDate.desc: The date that payment is due.

paymentMethod.desc: The name of the credit card or other method of payment for the order.

paymentMethodId.desc: An identifier for the method of payment used (e.g. the last 4 digits of the credit card).

paymentUrl.desc: The URL for sending a payment.

seller.desc: An entity which offers (sells / leases / lends / loans) the services / goods.  A seller may also be a provider.

http://schema.org/OrderAction.desc: An agent orders an object/product/service to be delivered/sent.

deliveryMethod.desc: A sub property of instrument. The method of delivery.

http://schema.org/OrderItem.desc: An order item is a line of an order. It includes the quantity and shipping details of a bought offer.

orderDelivery.desc: The delivery of the parcel related to this order or order item.

orderItemNumber.desc: The identifier of the order item.

orderItemStatus.desc: The current status of the order item.

orderQuantity.desc: The number of the item ordered. If the property is not set, assume the quantity is one.

http://schema.org/Organization.desc: An organization such as a school, NGO, corporation, club, etc.

aggregateRating.desc: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

areaServed.desc: The geographic area where a service or offered item is provided.

award.desc: An award won by or for this item.

awards.desc: Awards won by or for this item.

brand.desc: The brand(s) associated with a product or service, or the brand(s) maintained by an organization or business person.

contactPoint.desc: A contact point for a person or organization.

contactPoints.desc: A contact point for a person or organization.

department.desc: A relationship between an organization and a department of that organization, also described as an organization (allowing different urls, logos, opening hours). For example: a store with a pharmacy, or a bakery with a cafe.

dissolutionDate.desc: The date that this organization was dissolved.

duns.desc: The Dun & Bradstreet DUNS number for identifying an organization or business person.

event.desc: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

events.desc: Upcoming or past events associated with this place or organization.

founder.desc: A person who founded this organization.

founders.desc: A person who founded this organization.

foundingDate.desc: The date that this organization was founded.

foundingLocation.desc: The place where the Organization was founded.

funder.desc: A person or organization that supports (sponsors) something through some kind of financial contribution.

globalLocationNumber.desc: The [Global Location Number](http://www.gs1.org/gln) (GLN, sometimes also referred to as International Location Number or ILN) of the respective organization, person, or place. The GLN is a 13-digit number used to identify parties and physical locations.

hasOfferCatalog.desc: Indicates an OfferCatalog listing for this Organization, Person, or Service.

hasPOS.desc: Points-of-Sales operated by the organization or person.

isicV4.desc: The International Standard of Industrial Classification of All Economic Activities (ISIC), Revision 4 code for a particular organization, business person, or place.

legalName.desc: The official name of the organization, e.g. the registered company name.

leiCode.desc: An organization identifier that uniquely identifies a legal entity as defined in ISO 17442.

location.desc: The location of for example where the event is happening, an organization is located, or where an action takes place.

makesOffer.desc: A pointer to products or services offered by the organization or person.

member.desc: A member of an Organization or a ProgramMembership. Organizations can be members of organizations; ProgramMembership is typically for individuals.

memberOf.desc: An Organization (or ProgramMembership) to which this Person or Organization belongs.

naics.desc: The North American Industry Classification System (NAICS) code for a particular organization or business person.

numberOfEmployees.desc: The number of employees in an organization e.g. business.

owns.desc: Products owned by the organization or person.

parentOrganization.desc: The larger organization that this organization is a [[subOrganization]] of, if any.

publishingPrinciples.desc:
The publishingPrinciples property indicates (typically via [[URL]]) a document describing the editorial principles of an [[Organization]] (or individual e.g. a [[Person]] writing a blog) that relate to their activities as a publisher, e.g. ethics or diversity policies. When applied to a [[CreativeWork]] (e.g. [[NewsArticle]]) the principles are those of the party primarily responsible for the creation of the [[CreativeWork]].

While such policies are most typically expressed in natural language, sometimes related information (e.g. indicating a [[funder]]) can be expressed using schema.org terminology.

seeks.desc: A pointer to products or services sought by the organization or person (demand).

serviceArea.desc: The geographic area where the service is provided.

slogan.desc: A slogan or motto associated with the item.

sponsor.desc: A person or organization that supports a thing through a pledge, promise, or financial contribution. e.g. a sponsor of a Medical Study or a corporate sponsor of an event.

subOrganization.desc: A relationship between two organizations where the first includes the second, e.g., as a subsidiary. See also: the more specific 'department' property.

taxID.desc: The Tax / Fiscal ID of the organization or person, e.g. the TIN in the US or the CIF/NIF in Spain.

vatID.desc: The Value-added Tax ID of the organization or person.

http://schema.org/OrganizationRole.desc: A subclass of Role used to describe roles within organizations.

numberedPosition.desc: A number associated with a role in an organization, for example, the number on an athlete's jersey.

http://schema.org/OrganizeAction.desc: The act of manipulating/administering/supervising/controlling one or more objects.

http://schema.org/OwnershipInfo.desc: A structured value providing information about when a certain organization or person owned a certain product.

acquiredFrom.desc: The organization or person from which the product was acquired.

ownedFrom.desc: The date and time of obtaining the product.

ownedThrough.desc: The date and time of giving up ownership on the product.

typeOfGood.desc: The product that this structured value is referring to.

http://schema.org/PaintAction.desc: The act of producing a painting, typically with paint and canvas as instruments.

http://schema.org/ParcelDelivery.desc: The delivery of a parcel either via the postal service or a commercial service.

carrier.desc: 'carrier' is an out-dated term indicating the 'provider' for parcel delivery and flights.

deliveryStatus.desc: New entry added as the package passes through each leg of its journey (from shipment to final delivery).

expectedArrivalFrom.desc: The earliest date the package may arrive.

expectedArrivalUntil.desc: The latest date the package may arrive.

hasDeliveryMethod.desc: Method used for delivery or shipping.

partOfOrder.desc: The overall order the items in this delivery were included in.

provider.desc: The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.

trackingUrl.desc: Tracking url for the parcel delivery.

http://schema.org/ParcelService.desc:
A private parcel service as the delivery mode available for a certain offer.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DHL
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#FederalExpress
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#UPS

http://schema.org/ParentAudience.desc: A set of characteristics describing parents, who can be interested in viewing some content.

http://schema.org/ParkingFacility.desc: A parking lot or other parking facility.

http://schema.org/PawnShop.desc: A shop that will buy, or lend money against the security of, personal possessions.

http://schema.org/PayAction.desc: An agent pays a price to a participant.

recipient.desc: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

http://schema.org/PaymentCard.desc: A payment method using a credit, debit, store or other card to associate the payment with an account.

http://schema.org/PaymentChargeSpecifica.desc: The costs of settling the payment using a particular payment method.

appliesToDeliveryMethod.desc: The delivery method(s) to which the delivery charge or payment charge specification applies.

appliesToPaymentMethod.desc: The payment method(s) to which the payment charge specification applies.

http://schema.org/PaymentMethod.desc:
A payment method is a standardized procedure for transferring the monetary amount for a purchase. Payment methods are characterized by the legal and technical structures used, and by the organization or group carrying out the transaction.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ByBankTransferInAdvance
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ByInvoice
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Cash
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#CheckInAdvance
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#COD
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DirectDebit
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#GoogleCheckout
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PayPal
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PaySwarm

http://schema.org/PaymentService.desc: A Service to transfer funds from a person or organization to a beneficiary person or organization.

http://schema.org/PaymentStatusType.desc: A specific payment status. For example, PaymentDue, PaymentComplete, etc.

http://schema.org/PeopleAudience.desc: A set of characteristics belonging to people, e.g. who compose an item's target audience.

requiredGender.desc: Audiences defined by a person's gender.

requiredMaxAge.desc: Audiences defined by a person's maximum age.

requiredMinAge.desc: Audiences defined by a person's minimum age.

suggestedGender.desc: The gender of the person or audience.

suggestedMaxAge.desc: Maximal age recommended for viewing content.

suggestedMinAge.desc: Minimal age recommended for viewing content.

http://schema.org/PerformAction.desc: The act of participating in performance arts.

entertainmentBusiness.desc: A sub property of location. The entertainment business where the action occurred.

http://schema.org/PerformanceRole.desc: A PerformanceRole is a Role that some entity places with regard to a theatrical performance, e.g. in a Movie, TVSeries etc.

characterName.desc: The name of a character played in some acting or performing role, i.e. in a PerformanceRole.

http://schema.org/PerformingArtsTheater.desc: A theater or other performing art center.

http://schema.org/PerformingGroup.desc: A performance group, such as a band, an orchestra, or a circus.

http://schema.org/Periodical.desc: A publication in any medium issued in successive parts bearing numerical or chronological designations and intended, such as a magazine, scholarly journal, or newspaper to continue indefinitely.\n\nSee also [blog post](http://blog.schema.org/2014/09/schemaorg-support-for-bibliographic_2.html).

http://schema.org/Permit.desc: A permit issued by an organization, e.g. a parking pass.

issuedBy.desc: The organization issuing the ticket or permit.

issuedThrough.desc: The service through with the permit was granted.

permitAudience.desc: The target audience for this permit.

validFor.desc: The duration of validity of a permit or similar thing.

validFrom.desc: The date when the item becomes valid.

validIn.desc: The geographic area where a permit or similar thing is valid.

validUntil.desc: The date when the item is no longer valid.

http://schema.org/Person.desc: A person (alive, dead, undead, or fictional).

additionalName.desc: An additional name for a Person, can be used for a middle name.

affiliation.desc: An organization that this person is affiliated with. For example, a school/university, a club, or a team.

alumniOf.desc: An organization that the person is an alumni of.

award.desc: An award won by or for this item.

awards.desc: Awards won by or for this item.
