birthPlace.desc: The place where the person was born.

brand.desc: The brand(s) associated with a product or service, or the brand(s) maintained by an organization or business person.

contactPoint.desc: A contact point for a person or organization.

contactPoints.desc: A contact point for a person or organization.

deathPlace.desc: The place where the person died.

duns.desc: The Dun & Bradstreet DUNS number for identifying an organization or business person.

familyName.desc: Family name. In the U.S., the last name of an Person. This can be used along with givenName instead of the name property.

follows.desc: The most generic uni-directional social relation.

funder.desc: A person or organization that supports (sponsors) something through some kind of financial contribution.

gender.desc: Gender of the person. While http://schema.org/Male and http://schema.org/Female may be used, text strings are also acceptable for people who do not identify as a binary gender.

givenName.desc: Given name. In the U.S., the first name of a Person. This can be used along with familyName instead of the name property.

globalLocationNumber.desc: The [Global Location Number](http://www.gs1.org/gln) (GLN, sometimes also referred to as International Location Number or ILN) of the respective organization, person, or place. The GLN is a 13-digit number used to identify parties and physical locations.

hasOccupation.desc: The Person's occupation. For past professions, use Role for expressing dates.

hasOfferCatalog.desc: Indicates an OfferCatalog listing for this Organization, Person, or Service.

hasPOS.desc: Points-of-Sales operated by the organization or person.

homeLocation.desc: A contact location for a person's residence.

honorificPrefix.desc: An honorific prefix preceding a Person's name such as Dr/Mrs/Mr.

honorificSuffix.desc: An honorific suffix preceding a Person's name such as M.D. /PhD/MSCSW.

isicV4.desc: The International Standard of Industrial Classification of All Economic Activities (ISIC), Revision 4 code for a particular organization, business person, or place.

jobTitle.desc: The job title of the person (for example, Financial Manager).

knows.desc: The most generic bi-directional social/work relation.

makesOffer.desc: A pointer to products or services offered by the organization or person.

memberOf.desc: An Organization (or ProgramMembership) to which this Person or Organization belongs.

naics.desc: The North American Industry Classification System (NAICS) code for a particular organization or business person.

netWorth.desc: The total financial value of the person as calculated by subtracting assets from liabilities.

owns.desc: Products owned by the organization or person.

performerIn.desc: Event that this person is a performer or participant in.

publishingPrinciples.desc:
The publishingPrinciples property indicates (typically via [[URL]]) a document describing the editorial principles of an [[Organization]] (or individual e.g. a [[Person]] writing a blog) that relate to their activities as a publisher, e.g. ethics or diversity policies. When applied to a [[CreativeWork]] (e.g. [[NewsArticle]]) the principles are those of the party primarily responsible for the creation of the [[CreativeWork]].

While such policies are most typically expressed in natural language, sometimes related information (e.g. indicating a [[funder]]) can be expressed using schema.org terminology.

seeks.desc: A pointer to products or services sought by the organization or person (demand).

sponsor.desc: A person or organization that supports a thing through a pledge, promise, or financial contribution. e.g. a sponsor of a Medical Study or a corporate sponsor of an event.

taxID.desc: The Tax / Fiscal ID of the organization or person, e.g. the TIN in the US or the CIF/NIF in Spain.

vatID.desc: The Value-added Tax ID of the organization or person.

weight.desc: The weight of the product or person.

workLocation.desc: A contact location for a person's place of work.

worksFor.desc: Organizations that the person works for.

http://schema.org/PhotographAction.desc: The act of capturing still images of objects using a camera.

http://schema.org/Place.desc: Entities that have a somewhat fixed, physical extension.

additionalProperty.desc: A property-value pair representing an additional characteristics of the entitity, e.g. a product feature or another characteristic for which there is no matching property in schema.org.\n\nNote: Publishers should be aware that applications designed to use specific schema.org properties (e.g. http://schema.org/width, http://schema.org/color, http://schema.org/gtin13, ...) will typically expect such data to be provided using those properties, rather than using the generic property/value mechanism.

aggregateRating.desc: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

amenityFeature.desc: An amenity feature (e.g. a characteristic or service) of the Accommodation. This generic property does not make a statement about whether the feature is included in an offer for the main accommodation or available at extra costs.

branchCode.desc: A short textual code (also called "store code") that uniquely identifies a place of business. The code is typically assigned by the parentOrganization and used in structured URLs.\n\nFor example, in the URL http://www.starbucks.co.uk/store-locator/etc/detail/3047 the code "3047" is a branchCode for a particular branch.

containedIn.desc: The basic containment relation between a place and one that contains it.

containedInPlace.desc: The basic containment relation between a place and one that contains it.

containsPlace.desc: The basic containment relation between a place and another that it contains.

event.desc: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

events.desc: Upcoming or past events associated with this place or organization.

geo.desc: The geo coordinates of the place.

globalLocationNumber.desc: The [Global Location Number](http://www.gs1.org/gln) (GLN, sometimes also referred to as International Location Number or ILN) of the respective organization, person, or place. The GLN is a 13-digit number used to identify parties and physical locations.

hasMap.desc: A URL to a map of the place.

isAccessibleForFree.desc: A flag to signal that the item, event, or place is accessible for free.

isicV4.desc: The International Standard of Industrial Classification of All Economic Activities (ISIC), Revision 4 code for a particular organization, business person, or place.

map.desc: A URL to a map of the place.

maps.desc: A URL to a map of the place.

maximumAttendeeCapacity.desc: The total number of individuals that may attend an event or venue.

openingHoursSpecification.desc: The opening hours of a certain place.

publicAccess.desc: A flag to signal that the [[Place]] is open to public visitors.  If this property is omitted there is no assumed default boolean value

slogan.desc: A slogan or motto associated with the item.

smokingAllowed.desc: Indicates whether it is allowed to smoke in the place, e.g. in the restaurant, hotel or hotel room.

specialOpeningHoursSpecification.desc: The special opening hours of a certain place.\n\nUse this to explicitly override general opening hours brought in scope by [[openingHoursSpecification]] or [[openingHours]].

http://schema.org/PlaceOfWorship.desc: Place of worship, such as a church, synagogue, or mosque.

http://schema.org/PlanAction.desc: The act of planning the execution of an event/task/action/reservation/plan to a future date.

scheduledTime.desc: The time the object is scheduled to.

http://schema.org/PlayAction.desc:
The act of playing/exercising/training/performing for enjoyment, leisure, recreation, Competition or exercise.

Related actions:

* [[ListenAction]]: Unlike ListenAction (which is under ConsumeAction), PlayAction refers to performing for an audience or at an event, rather than consuming music.
* [[WatchAction]]: Unlike WatchAction (which is under ConsumeAction), PlayAction refers to showing/displaying for an audience or at an event, rather than consuming visual content.

audience.desc: An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.

event.desc: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

addressCountry.desc: The country. For example, USA. You can also provide the two-letter [ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166-1).

addressLocality.desc: The locality. For example, Mountain View.

postOfficeBoxNumber.desc: The post office box number for PO box addresses.

streetAddress.desc: The street address. For example, 1600 Amphitheatre Pkwy.

http://schema.org/PreOrderAction.desc: An agent orders a (not yet released) object/product/service to be delivered/sent.

http://schema.org/PrependAction.desc: The act of inserting at the beginning if an ordered collection.

http://schema.org/PresentationDigitalDoc.desc: A file containing slides or used for a presentation.

http://schema.org/PriceSpecification.desc: A structured value representing a price or price range. Typically, only the subclasses of this type are used for markup. It is recommended to use [[MonetaryAmount]] to describe independent amounts of money such as a salary, credit card limits, etc.

eligibleQuantity.desc: The interval and unit of measurement of ordering quantities for which the offer or price specification is valid. This allows e.g. specifying that a certain freight charge is valid only for a certain quantity.

eligibleTransactionVolume.desc: The transaction volume, in a monetary unit, for which the offer or price specification is valid, e.g. for indicating a minimal purchasing volume, to express free shipping above a certain order volume, or to limit the acceptance of credit cards to purchases to a certain minimal amount.

maxPrice.desc: The highest price if the price is a range.

minPrice.desc: The lowest price if the price is a range.

price.desc:
The offer price of a product, or of a price component when attached to PriceSpecification and its subtypes.

Usage guidelines:

* Use the [[priceCurrency]] property (with standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR") instead of including [ambiguous symbols](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dollar_sign#Currencies_that_use_the_dollar_or_peso_sign) such as '$' in the value.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.
* Note that both [RDFa](http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-primer/#using-the-content-attribute) and Microdata syntax allow the use of a "content=" attribute for publishing simple machine-readable values alongside more human-friendly formatting.
* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.

priceCurrency.desc: The currency of the price, or a price component when attached to [[PriceSpecification]] and its subtypes.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

validFrom.desc: The date when the item becomes valid.

validThrough.desc: The date after when the item is not valid. For example the end of an offer, salary period, or a period of opening hours.

valueAddedTaxIncluded.desc: Specifies whether the applicable value-added tax (VAT) is included in the price specification or not.

http://schema.org/Product.desc: Any offered product or service. For example: a pair of shoes; a concert ticket; the rental of a car; a haircut; or an episode of a TV show streamed online.

additionalProperty.desc: A property-value pair representing an additional characteristics of the entitity, e.g. a product feature or another characteristic for which there is no matching property in schema.org.\n\nNote: Publishers should be aware that applications designed to use specific schema.org properties (e.g. http://schema.org/width, http://schema.org/color, http://schema.org/gtin13, ...) will typically expect such data to be provided using those properties, rather than using the generic property/value mechanism.

aggregateRating.desc: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

audience.desc: An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.

award.desc: An award won by or for this item.

awards.desc: Awards won by or for this item.

brand.desc: The brand(s) associated with a product or service, or the brand(s) maintained by an organization or business person.

category.desc: A category for the item. Greater signs or slashes can be used to informally indicate a category hierarchy.

gtin12.desc: The GTIN-12 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. The GTIN-12 is the 12-digit GS1 Identification Key composed of a U.P.C. Company Prefix, Item Reference, and Check Digit used to identify trade items. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

gtin13.desc: The GTIN-13 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This is equivalent to 13-digit ISBN codes and EAN UCC-13. Former 12-digit UPC codes can be converted into a GTIN-13 code by simply adding a preceeding zero. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

gtin14.desc: The GTIN-14 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

gtin8.desc: The [GTIN-8](http://apps.gs1.org/GDD/glossary/Pages/GTIN-8.aspx) code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This code is also known as EAN/UCC-8 or 8-digit EAN. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

isAccessoryOrSparePartFor.desc: A pointer to another product (or multiple products) for which this product is an accessory or spare part.

isConsumableFor.desc: A pointer to another product (or multiple products) for which this product is a consumable.

isRelatedTo.desc: A pointer to another, somehow related product (or multiple products).

isSimilarTo.desc: A pointer to another, functionally similar product (or multiple products).

itemCondition.desc: A predefined value from OfferItemCondition or a textual description of the condition of the product or service, or the products or services included in the offer.

material.desc: A material that something is made from, e.g. leather, wool, cotton, paper.

model.desc: The model of the product. Use with the URL of a ProductModel or a textual representation of the model identifier. The URL of the ProductModel can be from an external source. It is recommended to additionally provide strong product identifiers via the gtin8/gtin13/gtin14 and mpn properties.

mpn.desc: The Manufacturer Part Number (MPN) of the product, or the product to which the offer refers.

offers.desc: An offer to provide this itemfor example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event.

productID.desc: The product identifier, such as ISBN. For example: ``` meta itemprop="productID" content="isbn:123-456-789" ```.

productionDate.desc: The date of production of the item, e.g. vehicle.

purchaseDate.desc: The date the item e.g. vehicle was purchased by the current owner.

releaseDate.desc: The release date of a product or product model. This can be used to distinguish the exact variant of a product.

sku.desc: The Stock Keeping Unit (SKU), i.e. a merchant-specific identifier for a product or service, or the product to which the offer refers.

slogan.desc: A slogan or motto associated with the item.

weight.desc: The weight of the product or person.

http://schema.org/ProductModel.desc: A datasheet or vendor specification of a product (in the sense of a prototypical description).

isVariantOf.desc: A pointer to a base product from which this product is a variant. It is safe to infer that the variant inherits all product features from the base model, unless defined locally. This is not transitive.

predecessorOf.desc: A pointer from a previous, often discontinued variant of the product to its newer variant.

successorOf.desc: A pointer from a newer variant of a product  to its previous, often discontinued predecessor.

http://schema.org/ProfessionalService.desc:
Original definition: "provider of professional services."\n\nThe general [[ProfessionalService]] type for local businesses was deprecated due to confusion with [[Service]]. For reference, the types that it included were: [[Dentist]],
        [[AccountingService]], [[Attorney]], [[Notary]], as well as types for several kinds of [[HomeAndConstructionBusiness]]: [[Electrician]], [[GeneralContractor]],
        [[HousePainter]], [[Locksmith]], [[Plumber]], [[RoofingContractor]]. [[LegalService]] was introduced as a more inclusive supertype of [[Attorney]].

http://schema.org/ProgramMembership.desc: Used to describe membership in a loyalty programs (e.g. "StarAliance"), traveler clubs (e.g. "AAA"), purchase clubs ("Safeway Club"), etc.

hostingOrganization.desc: The organization (airline, travelers' club, etc.) the membership is made with.

member.desc: A member of an Organization or a ProgramMembership. Organizations can be members of organizations; ProgramMembership is typically for individuals.

membershipNumber.desc: A unique identifier for the membership.

http://schema.org/PropertyValue.desc: A property-value pair, e.g. representing a feature of a product or place. Use the 'name' property for the name of the property. If there is an additional human-readable version of the value, put that into the 'description' property.\n\n Always use specific schema.org properties when a) they exist and b) you can populate them. Using PropertyValue as a substitute will typically not trigger the same effect as using the original, specific property.

maxValue.desc: The upper value of some characteristic or property.

minValue.desc: The lower value of some characteristic or property.

propertyID.desc:
A commonly used identifier for the characteristic represented by the property, e.g. a manufacturer or a standard code for a property. propertyID can be
(1) a prefixed string, mainly meant to be used with standards for product properties; (2) a site-specific, non-prefixed string (e.g. the primary key of the property or the vendor-specific id of the property), or (3)
a URL indicating the type of the property, either pointing to an external vocabulary, or a Web resource that describes the property (e.g. a glossary entry).
Standards bodies should promote a standard prefix for the identifiers of properties from their standards.

unitCode.desc: The unit of measurement given using the UN/CEFACT Common Code (3 characters) or a URL. Other codes than the UN/CEFACT Common Code may be used with a prefix followed by a colon.

unitText.desc:
A string or text indicating the unit of measurement. Useful if you cannot provide a standard unit code for
unitCode.

value.desc:
The value of the quantitative value or property value node.

* For [[QuantitativeValue]] and [[MonetaryAmount]], the recommended type for values is 'Number'.
* For [[PropertyValue]], it can be 'Text;', 'Number', 'Boolean', or 'StructuredValue'.
* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.

valueReference.desc: A pointer to a secondary value that provides additional information on the original value, e.g. a reference temperature.

defaultValue.desc: The default value of the input.  For properties that expect a literal, the default is a literal value, for properties that expect an object, it's an ID reference to one of the current values.

maxValue.desc: The upper value of some characteristic or property.

minValue.desc: The lower value of some characteristic or property.

multipleValues.desc: Whether multiple values are allowed for the property.  Default is false.

readonlyValue.desc: Whether or not a property is mutable.  Default is false. Specifying this for a property that also has a value makes it act similar to a "hidden" input in an HTML form.

stepValue.desc: The stepValue attribute indicates the granularity that is expected (and required) of the value in a PropertyValueSpecification.

valueMaxLength.desc: Specifies the allowed range for number of characters in a literal value.

valueMinLength.desc: Specifies the minimum allowed range for number of characters in a literal value.

valueName.desc: Indicates the name of the PropertyValueSpecification to be used in URL templates and form encoding in a manner analogous to HTML's input@name.

valuePattern.desc: Specifies a regular expression for testing literal values according to the HTML spec.

valueRequired.desc: Whether the property must be filled in to complete the action.  Default is false.

http://schema.org/PublicationEvent.desc: A PublicationEvent corresponds indifferently to the event of publication for a CreativeWork of any type e.g. a broadcast event, an on-demand event, a book/journal publication via a variety of delivery media.

free.desc: A flag to signal that the item, event, or place is accessible for free.

isAccessibleForFree.desc: A flag to signal that the item, event, or place is accessible for free.

publishedOn.desc: A broadcast service associated with the publication event.

http://schema.org/PublicationIssue.desc: A part of a successively published publication such as a periodical or publication volume, often numbered, usually containing a grouping of works such as articles.\n\n[blog post](http://blog.schema.org/2014/09/schemaorg-support-for-bibliographic_2.html).

issueNumber.desc: Identifies the issue of publication; for example, "iii" or "2".

pageEnd.desc: The page on which the work ends; for example "138" or "xvi".

pageStart.desc: The page on which the work starts; for example "135" or "xiii".

pagination.desc: Any description of pages that is not separated into pageStart and pageEnd; for example, "1-6, 9, 55" or "10-12, 46-49".

http://schema.org/PublicationVolume.desc:
A part of a successively published publication such as a periodical or multi-volume work, often numbered. It may represent a time span, such as a year.

      See also blog post.

pageEnd.desc: The page on which the work ends; for example "138" or "xvi".

pageStart.desc: The page on which the work starts; for example "135" or "xiii".

pagination.desc: Any description of pages that is not separated into pageStart and pageEnd; for example, "1-6, 9, 55" or "10-12, 46-49".

volumeNumber.desc: Identifies the volume of publication or multi-part work; for example, "iii" or "2".

http://schema.org/QAPage.desc: A QAPage is a WebPage focussed on a specific Question and its Answer(s), e.g. in a question answering site or documenting Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs).

http://schema.org/QualitativeValue.desc: A predefined value for a product characteristic, e.g. the power cord plug type 'US' or the garment sizes 'S', 'M', 'L', and 'XL'.

additionalProperty.desc: A property-value pair representing an additional characteristics of the entitity, e.g. a product feature or another characteristic for which there is no matching property in schema.org.\n\nNote: Publishers should be aware that applications designed to use specific schema.org properties (e.g. http://schema.org/width, http://schema.org/color, http://schema.org/gtin13, ...) will typically expect such data to be provided using those properties, rather than using the generic property/value mechanism.

equal.desc: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is equal to the object.

greater.desc: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is greater than the object.

greaterOrEqual.desc: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is greater than or equal to the object.

lesser.desc: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is lesser than the object.

lesserOrEqual.desc: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is lesser than or equal to the object.

nonEqual.desc: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is not equal to the object.

valueReference.desc: A pointer to a secondary value that provides additional information on the original value, e.g. a reference temperature.

http://schema.org/QuantitativeValue.desc: A point value or interval for product characteristics and other purposes.

additionalProperty.desc: A property-value pair representing an additional characteristics of the entitity, e.g. a product feature or another characteristic for which there is no matching property in schema.org.\n\nNote: Publishers should be aware that applications designed to use specific schema.org properties (e.g. http://schema.org/width, http://schema.org/color, http://schema.org/gtin13, ...) will typically expect such data to be provided using those properties, rather than using the generic property/value mechanism.

maxValue.desc: The upper value of some characteristic or property.

minValue.desc: The lower value of some characteristic or property.

unitCode.desc: The unit of measurement given using the UN/CEFACT Common Code (3 characters) or a URL. Other codes than the UN/CEFACT Common Code may be used with a prefix followed by a colon.

unitText.desc:
A string or text indicating the unit of measurement. Useful if you cannot provide a standard unit code for
unitCode.

value.desc:
The value of the quantitative value or property value node.

* For [[QuantitativeValue]] and [[MonetaryAmount]], the recommended type for values is 'Number'.
* For [[PropertyValue]], it can be 'Text;', 'Number', 'Boolean', or 'StructuredValue'.
* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.

valueReference.desc: A pointer to a secondary value that provides additional information on the original value, e.g. a reference temperature.

duration.desc: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

http://schema.org/Quantity.desc: Quantities such as distance, time, mass, weight, etc. Particular instances of say Mass are entities like '3 Kg' or '4 milligrams'.

http://schema.org/Question.desc: A specific question - e.g. from a user seeking answers online, or collected in a Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ) document.

acceptedAnswer.desc: The answer(s) that has been accepted as best, typically on a Question/Answer site. Sites vary in their selection mechanisms, e.g. drawing on community opinion and/or the view of the Question author.

answerCount.desc: The number of answers this question has received.

downvoteCount.desc: The number of downvotes this question, answer or comment has received from the community.

suggestedAnswer.desc: An answer (possibly one of several, possibly incorrect) to a Question, e.g. on a Question/Answer site.

upvoteCount.desc: The number of upvotes this question, answer or comment has received from the community.

http://schema.org/QuoteAction.desc: An agent quotes/estimates/appraises an object/product/service with a price at a location/store.

http://schema.org/RVPark.desc: A place offering space for "Recreational Vehicles", Caravans, mobile homes and the like.

http://schema.org/RadioChannel.desc: A unique instance of a radio BroadcastService on a CableOrSatelliteService lineup.

http://schema.org/RadioClip.desc: A short radio program or a segment/part of a radio program.

http://schema.org/RadioEpisode.desc: A radio episode which can be part of a series or season.

http://schema.org/RadioSeason.desc: Season dedicated to radio broadcast and associated online delivery.

http://schema.org/RadioSeries.desc: CreativeWorkSeries dedicated to radio broadcast and associated online delivery.

actor.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

actors.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

containsSeason.desc: A season that is part of the media series.

director.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

directors.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

episode.desc: An episode of a tv, radio or game media within a series or season.

episodes.desc: An episode of a TV/radio series or season.

numberOfEpisodes.desc: The number of episodes in this season or series.

numberOfSeasons.desc: The number of seasons in this series.

productionCompany.desc: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

season.desc: A season in a media series.

seasons.desc: A season in a media series.

trailer.desc: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

http://schema.org/Rating.desc: A rating is an evaluation on a numeric scale, such as 1 to 5 stars.

author.desc: The author of this content or rating. Please note that author is special in that HTML 5 provides a special mechanism for indicating authorship via the rel tag. That is equivalent to this and may be used interchangeably.

bestRating.desc: The highest value allowed in this rating system. If bestRating is omitted, 5 is assumed.

ratingValue.desc:
The rating for the content.

Usage guidelines:

* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.

reviewAspect.desc: This Review or Rating is relevant to this part or facet of the itemReviewed.

worstRating.desc: The lowest value allowed in this rating system. If worstRating is omitted, 1 is assumed.

http://schema.org/ReactAction.desc: The act of responding instinctively and emotionally to an object, expressing a sentiment.

http://schema.org/ReadAction.desc: The act of consuming written content.

http://schema.org/ReceiveAction.desc:
The act of physically/electronically taking delivery of an object thathas been transferred from an origin to a destination. Reciprocal of SendAction.

Related actions:

* [[SendAction]]: The reciprocal of ReceiveAction.
* [[TakeAction]]: Unlike TakeAction, ReceiveAction does not imply that the ownership has been transfered (e.g. I can receive a package, but it does not mean the package is now mine).

deliveryMethod.desc: A sub property of instrument. The method of delivery.

sender.desc: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the sending end of the action.

http://schema.org/Recipe.desc: A recipe. For dietary restrictions covered by the recipe, a few common restrictions are enumerated via [[suitableForDiet]]. The [[keywords]] property can also be used to add more detail.

cookTime.desc: The time it takes to actually cook the dish, in [ISO 8601 duration format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

cookingMethod.desc: The method of cooking, such as Frying, Steaming, ...

ingredients.desc: A single ingredient used in the recipe, e.g. sugar, flour or garlic.

nutrition.desc: Nutrition information about the recipe or menu item.

recipeCategory.desc: The category of the recipefor example, appetizer, entree, etc.

recipeCuisine.desc: The cuisine of the recipe (for example, French or Ethiopian).

recipeIngredient.desc: A single ingredient used in the recipe, e.g. sugar, flour or garlic.

recipeInstructions.desc: A step in making the recipe, in the form of a single item (document, video, etc.) or an ordered list with HowToStep and/or HowToSection items.

recipeYield.desc: The quantity produced by the recipe (for example, number of people served, number of servings, etc).

suitableForDiet.desc: Indicates a dietary restriction or guideline for which this recipe or menu item is suitable, e.g. diabetic, halal etc.

http://schema.org/RegisterAction.desc:
The act of registering to be a user of a service, product or web page.

Related actions:

* [[JoinAction]]: Unlike JoinAction, RegisterAction implies you are registering to be a user of a service, *not* a group/team of people.
* [FollowAction]]: Unlike FollowAction, RegisterAction doesn't imply that the agent is expecting to poll for updates from the object.
* [[SubscribeAction]]: Unlike SubscribeAction, RegisterAction doesn't imply that the agent is expecting updates from the object.

http://schema.org/RejectAction.desc:
The act of rejecting to/adopting an object.

Related actions:

* [[AcceptAction]]: The antonym of RejectAction.

http://schema.org/RentAction.desc: The act of giving money in return for temporary use, but not ownership, of an object such as a vehicle or property. For example, an agent rents a property from a landlord in exchange for a periodic payment.

landlord.desc: A sub property of participant. The owner of the real estate property.

realEstateAgent.desc: A sub property of participant. The real estate agent involved in the action.

http://schema.org/RentalCarReservation.desc: A reservation for a rental car.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations.

dropoffLocation.desc: Where a rental car can be dropped off.

dropoffTime.desc: When a rental car can be dropped off.

pickupLocation.desc: Where a taxi will pick up a passenger or a rental car can be picked up.

pickupTime.desc: When a taxi will pickup a passenger or a rental car can be picked up.

http://schema.org/ReplaceAction.desc: The act of editing a recipient by replacing an old object with a new object.

replacee.desc: A sub property of object. The object that is being replaced.

replacer.desc: A sub property of object. The object that replaces.

http://schema.org/ReplyAction.desc:
The act of responding to a question/message asked/sent by the object. Related to [[AskAction]]

Related actions:

* [[AskAction]]: Appears generally as an origin of a ReplyAction.

resultComment.desc: A sub property of result. The Comment created or sent as a result of this action.

http://schema.org/Report.desc: A Report generated by governmental or non-governmental organization.

reportNumber.desc: The number or other unique designator assigned to a Report by the publishing organization.

http://schema.org/Reservation.desc: Describes a reservation for travel, dining or an event. Some reservations require tickets. \n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, restaurant reservations, flights, or rental cars, use [[Offer]].

bookingAgent.desc: 'bookingAgent' is an out-dated term indicating a 'broker' that serves as a booking agent.

bookingTime.desc: The date and time the reservation was booked.

broker.desc: An entity that arranges for an exchange between a buyer and a seller.  In most cases a broker never acquires or releases ownership of a product or service involved in an exchange.  If it is not clear whether an entity is a broker, seller, or buyer, the latter two terms are preferred.

modifiedTime.desc: The date and time the reservation was modified.

priceCurrency.desc: The currency of the price, or a price component when attached to [[PriceSpecification]] and its subtypes.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

programMembershipUsed.desc: Any membership in a frequent flyer, hotel loyalty program, etc. being applied to the reservation.

provider.desc: The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.

reservationFor.desc: The thing -- flight, event, restaurant,etc. being reserved.

reservationId.desc: A unique identifier for the reservation.

reservationStatus.desc: The current status of the reservation.

reservedTicket.desc: A ticket associated with the reservation.

totalPrice.desc:
The total price for the reservation or ticket, including applicable taxes, shipping, etc.

Usage guidelines:

* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.

underName.desc: The person or organization the reservation or ticket is for.

http://schema.org/ReservationPackage.desc: A group of multiple reservations with common values for all sub-reservations.

subReservation.desc: The individual reservations included in the package. Typically a repeated property.

http://schema.org/ReserveAction.desc:
Reserving a concrete object.

Related actions:

* [[ScheduleAction]]: Unlike ScheduleAction, ReserveAction reserves concrete objects (e.g. a table, a hotel) towards a time slot / spatial allocation.

http://schema.org/Reservoir.desc: A reservoir of water, typically an artificially created lake, like the Lake Kariba reservoir.

http://schema.org/Residence.desc: The place where a person lives.

http://schema.org/Resort.desc:
A resort is a place used for relaxation or recreation, attracting visitors for holidays or vacations. Resorts are places, towns or sometimes commercial establishment operated by a single company (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Resort).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

http://schema.org/RestrictedDiet.desc: A diet restricted to certain foods or preparations for cultural, religious, health or lifestyle reasons.

http://schema.org/ResumeAction.desc: The act of resuming a device or application which was formerly paused (e.g. resume music playback or resume a timer).

http://schema.org/ReturnAction.desc: The act of returning to the origin that which was previously received (concrete objects) or taken (ownership).

recipient.desc: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

http://schema.org/Review.desc: A review of an item - for example, of a restaurant, movie, or store.

itemReviewed.desc: The item that is being reviewed/rated.

reviewAspect.desc: This Review or Rating is relevant to this part or facet of the itemReviewed.

reviewBody.desc: The actual body of the review.

reviewRating.desc: The rating given in this review. Note that reviews can themselves be rated. The ```reviewRating``` applies to rating given by the review. The [[aggregateRating]] property applies to the review itself, as a creative work.

http://schema.org/ReviewAction.desc: The act of producing a balanced opinion about the object for an audience. An agent reviews an object with participants resulting in a review.

resultReview.desc: A sub property of result. The review that resulted in the performing of the action.

http://schema.org/RiverBodyOfWater.desc: A river (for example, the broad majestic Shannon).

http://schema.org/Role.desc: Represents additional information about a relationship or property. For example a Role can be used to say that a 'member' role linking some SportsTeam to a player occurred during a particular time period. Or that a Person's 'actor' role in a Movie was for some particular characterName. Such properties can be attached to a Role entity, which is then associated with the main entities using ordinary properties like 'member' or 'actor'.\n\nSee also [blog post](http://blog.schema.org/2014/06/introducing-role.html).

endDate.desc: The end date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

namedPosition.desc: A position played, performed or filled by a person or organization, as part of an organization. For example, an athlete in a SportsTeam might play in the position named 'Quarterback'.

roleName.desc: A role played, performed or filled by a person or organization. For example, the team of creators for a comic book might fill the roles named 'inker', 'penciller', and 'letterer'; or an athlete in a SportsTeam might play in the position named 'Quarterback'.

startDate.desc: The start date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

http://schema.org/Room.desc:
A room is a distinguishable space within a structure, usually separated from other spaces by interior walls. (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Room).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

http://schema.org/RsvpAction.desc: The act of notifying an event organizer as to whether you expect to attend the event.

additionalNumberOfGuests.desc: If responding yes, the number of guests who will attend in addition to the invitee.

rsvpResponse.desc: The response (yes, no, maybe) to the RSVP.

http://schema.org/RsvpResponseType.desc: RsvpResponseType is an enumeration type whose instances represent responding to an RSVP request.

http://schema.org/ScheduleAction.desc:
Scheduling future actions, events, or tasks.

Related actions:

* [[ReserveAction]]: Unlike ReserveAction, ScheduleAction allocates future actions (e.g. an event, a task, etc) towards a time slot / spatial allocation.

http://schema.org/ScreeningEvent.desc: A screening of a movie or other video.

subtitleLanguage.desc: Languages in which subtitles/captions are available, in [IETF BCP 47 standard format](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47).

videoFormat.desc: The type of screening or video broadcast used (e.g. IMAX, 3D, SD, HD, etc.).

workPresented.desc: The movie presented during this event.

http://schema.org/SeaBodyOfWater.desc: A sea (for example, the Caspian sea).

http://schema.org/SearchAction.desc:
The act of searching for an object.

Related actions:

* [[FindAction]]: SearchAction generally leads to a FindAction, but not necessarily.

query.desc: A sub property of instrument. The query used on this action.

http://schema.org/SearchResultsPage.desc: Web page type: Search results page.

http://schema.org/Season.desc: A media season e.g. tv, radio, video game etc.

http://schema.org/Seat.desc: Used to describe a seat, such as a reserved seat in an event reservation.

seatNumber.desc: The location of the reserved seat (e.g., 27).

seatRow.desc: The row location of the reserved seat (e.g., B).

seatSection.desc: The section location of the reserved seat (e.g. Orchestra).

http://schema.org/SellAction.desc: The act of taking money from a buyer in exchange for goods or services rendered. An agent sells an object, product, or service to a buyer for a price. Reciprocal of BuyAction.

buyer.desc: A sub property of participant. The participant/person/organization that bought the object.

warrantyPromise.desc: The warranty promise(s) included in the offer.

http://schema.org/SendAction.desc:
The act of physically/electronically dispatching an object for transfer from an origin to a destination.Related actions:

* [[ReceiveAction]]: The reciprocal of SendAction.
* [[GiveAction]]: Unlike GiveAction, SendAction does not imply the transfer of ownership (e.g. I can send you my laptop, but I'm not necessarily giving it to you).

deliveryMethod.desc: A sub property of instrument. The method of delivery.

recipient.desc: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

http://schema.org/Series.desc: A Series in schema.org is a group of related items, typically but not necessarily of the same kind. See also [[CreativeWorkSeries]], [[EventSeries]].

http://schema.org/Service.desc: A service provided by an organization, e.g. delivery service, print services, etc.

aggregateRating.desc: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

areaServed.desc: The geographic area where a service or offered item is provided.

audience.desc: An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.

availableChannel.desc: A means of accessing the service (e.g. a phone bank, a web site, a location, etc.).

award.desc: An award won by or for this item.

brand.desc: The brand(s) associated with a product or service, or the brand(s) maintained by an organization or business person.

broker.desc: An entity that arranges for an exchange between a buyer and a seller.  In most cases a broker never acquires or releases ownership of a product or service involved in an exchange.  If it is not clear whether an entity is a broker, seller, or buyer, the latter two terms are preferred.

category.desc: A category for the item. Greater signs or slashes can be used to informally indicate a category hierarchy.

hasOfferCatalog.desc: Indicates an OfferCatalog listing for this Organization, Person, or Service.

hoursAvailable.desc: The hours during which this service or contact is available.

isRelatedTo.desc: A pointer to another, somehow related product (or multiple products).

isSimilarTo.desc: A pointer to another, functionally similar product (or multiple products).

offers.desc: An offer to provide this itemfor example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event.

produces.desc: The tangible thing generated by the service, e.g. a passport, permit, etc.

provider.desc: The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.

providerMobility.desc: Indicates the mobility of a provided service (e.g. 'static', 'dynamic').

serviceArea.desc: The geographic area where the service is provided.

serviceAudience.desc: The audience eligible for this service.

serviceOutput.desc: The tangible thing generated by the service, e.g. a passport, permit, etc.

serviceType.desc: The type of service being offered, e.g. veterans' benefits, emergency relief, etc.

slogan.desc: A slogan or motto associated with the item.

http://schema.org/ServiceChannel.desc: A means for accessing a service, e.g. a government office location, web site, or phone number.

availableLanguage.desc: A language someone may use with or at the item, service or place. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[inLanguage]]

processingTime.desc: Estimated processing time for the service using this channel.

providesService.desc: The service provided by this channel.

serviceLocation.desc: The location (e.g. civic structure, local business, etc.) where a person can go to access the service.

servicePhone.desc: The phone number to use to access the service.

servicePostalAddress.desc: The address for accessing the service by mail.

serviceSmsNumber.desc: The number to access the service by text message.

serviceUrl.desc: The website to access the service.

http://schema.org/ShareAction.desc: The act of distributing content to people for their amusement or edification.

numberOfRooms.desc:
The number of rooms (excluding bathrooms and closets) of the accommodation or lodging business.
Typical unit code(s): ROM for room or C62 for no unit. The type of room can be put in the unitText property of the QuantitativeValue.

occupancy.desc:
The allowed total occupancy for the accommodation in persons (including infants etc). For individual accommodations, this is not necessarily the legal maximum but defines the permitted usage as per the contractual agreement (e.g. a double room used by a single person).
Typical unit code(s): C62 for person

http://schema.org/SiteNavigationElement.desc: A navigation element of the page.

http://schema.org/SocialMediaPosting.desc: A post to a social media platform, including blog posts, tweets, Facebook posts, etc.

sharedContent.desc: A CreativeWork such as an image, video, or audio clip shared as part of this posting.

applicationCategory.desc: Type of software application, e.g. 'Game, Multimedia'.

applicationSubCategory.desc: Subcategory of the application, e.g. 'Arcade Game'.

applicationSuite.desc: The name of the application suite to which the application belongs (e.g. Excel belongs to Office).

availableOnDevice.desc: Device required to run the application. Used in cases where a specific make/model is required to run the application.

countriesNotSupported.desc: Countries for which the application is not supported. You can also provide the two-letter ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code.

countriesSupported.desc: Countries for which the application is supported. You can also provide the two-letter ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code.

device.desc: Device required to run the application. Used in cases where a specific make/model is required to run the application.

downloadUrl.desc: If the file can be downloaded, URL to download the binary.

featureList.desc: Features or modules provided by this application (and possibly required by other applications).

fileSize.desc: Size of the application / package (e.g. 18MB). In the absence of a unit (MB, KB etc.), KB will be assumed.

installUrl.desc: URL at which the app may be installed, if different from the URL of the item.

permissions.desc: Permission(s) required to run the app (for example, a mobile app may require full internet access or may run only on wifi).

processorRequirements.desc: Processor architecture required to run the application (e.g. IA64).

releaseNotes.desc: Description of what changed in this version.

requirements.desc: Component dependency requirements for application. This includes runtime environments and shared libraries that are not included in the application distribution package, but required to run the application (Examples: DirectX, Java or .NET runtime).

screenshot.desc: A link to a screenshot image of the app.

softwareAddOn.desc: Additional content for a software application.

softwareRequirements.desc: Component dependency requirements for application. This includes runtime environments and shared libraries that are not included in the application distribution package, but required to run the application (Examples: DirectX, Java or .NET runtime).

http://schema.org/SoftwareSourceCode.desc: Computer programming source code. Example: Full (compile ready) solutions, code snippet samples, scripts, templates.

codeRepository.desc: Link to the repository where the un-compiled, human readable code and related code is located (SVN, github, CodePlex).

codeSampleType.desc: What type of code sample: full (compile ready) solution, code snippet, inline code, scripts, template.

runtime.desc: Runtime platform or script interpreter dependencies (Example - Java v1, Python2.3, .Net Framework 3.0).

runtimePlatform.desc: Runtime platform or script interpreter dependencies (Example - Java v1, Python2.3, .Net Framework 3.0).

sampleType.desc: What type of code sample: full (compile ready) solution, code snippet, inline code, scripts, template.

targetProduct.desc: Target Operating System / Product to which the code applies.  If applies to several versions, just the product name can be used.

http://schema.org/SomeProducts.desc: A placeholder for multiple similar products of the same kind.

inventoryLevel.desc: The current approximate inventory level for the item or items.

http://schema.org/SpeakableSpecification.desc: A SpeakableSpecification indicates (typically via [[xpath]] or [[cssSelector]]) sections of a document that are highlighted as particularly [[speakable]]. Instances of this type are expected to be used primarily as values of the [[speakable]] property.

cssSelector.desc: A CSS selector, e.g. of a [[SpeakableSpecification]] or [[WebPageElement]]. In the latter case, multiple matches within a page can constitute a single conceptual "Web page element".

xpath.desc: An XPath, e.g. of a [[SpeakableSpecification]] or [[WebPageElement]]. In the latter case, multiple matches within a page can constitute a single conceptual "Web page element".

http://schema.org/Specialty.desc: Any branch of a field in which people typically develop specific expertise, usually after significant study, time, and effort.

http://schema.org/SportsActivityLocation.desc: A sports location, such as a playing field.

awayTeam.desc: The away team in a sports event.

competitor.desc: A competitor in a sports event.

homeTeam.desc: The home team in a sports event.

http://schema.org/SportsOrganization.desc: Represents the collection of all sports organizations, including sports teams, governing bodies, and sports associations.

athlete.desc: A person that acts as performing member of a sports team; a player as opposed to a coach.

coach.desc: A person that acts in a coaching role for a sports team.

http://schema.org/State.desc: A state or province of a country.

http://schema.org/SteeringPositionValue.desc: A value indicating a steering position.

http://schema.org/StructuredValue.desc: Structured values are used when the value of a property has a more complex structure than simply being a textual value or a reference to another thing.

http://schema.org/SubscribeAction.desc:
The act of forming a personal connection with someone/something (object) unidirectionally/asymmetrically to get updates pushed to.

Related actions:

* [[FollowAction]]: Unlike FollowAction, SubscribeAction implies that the subscriber acts as a passive agent being constantly/actively pushed for updates.
* [[RegisterAction]]: Unlike RegisterAction, SubscribeAction implies that the agent is interested in continuing receiving updates from the object.
* [[JoinAction]]: Unlike JoinAction, SubscribeAction implies that the agent is interested in continuing receiving updates from the object.

http://schema.org/Suite.desc:
A suite in a hotel or other public accommodation, denotes a class of luxury accommodations, the key feature of which is multiple rooms (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Suite_(hotel)).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

bed.desc:
The type of bed or beds included in the accommodation. For the single case of just one bed of a certain type, you use bed directly with a text.
      If you want to indicate the quantity of a certain kind of bed, use an instance of BedDetails. For more detailed information, use the amenityFeature property.

numberOfRooms.desc:
The number of rooms (excluding bathrooms and closets) of the accommodation or lodging business.
Typical unit code(s): ROM for room or C62 for no unit. The type of room can be put in the unitText property of the QuantitativeValue.

occupancy.desc:
The allowed total occupancy for the accommodation in persons (including infants etc). For individual accommodations, this is not necessarily the legal maximum but defines the permitted usage as per the contractual agreement (e.g. a double room used by a single person).
Typical unit code(s): C62 for person

http://schema.org/SuspendAction.desc: The act of momentarily pausing a device or application (e.g. pause music playback or pause a timer).

http://schema.org/TVClip.desc: A short TV program or a segment/part of a TV program.

partOfTVSeries.desc: The TV series to which this episode or season belongs.

http://schema.org/TVEpisode.desc: A TV episode which can be part of a series or season.

countryOfOrigin.desc: The country of the principal offices of the production company or individual responsible for the movie or program.

partOfTVSeries.desc: The TV series to which this episode or season belongs.

subtitleLanguage.desc: Languages in which subtitles/captions are available, in [IETF BCP 47 standard format](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47).

http://schema.org/TVSeason.desc: Season dedicated to TV broadcast and associated online delivery.

countryOfOrigin.desc: The country of the principal offices of the production company or individual responsible for the movie or program.

partOfTVSeries.desc: The TV series to which this episode or season belongs.

http://schema.org/TVSeries.desc: CreativeWorkSeries dedicated to TV broadcast and associated online delivery.

actor.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

actors.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

containsSeason.desc: A season that is part of the media series.

countryOfOrigin.desc: The country of the principal offices of the production company or individual responsible for the movie or program.

director.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

directors.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

episode.desc: An episode of a tv, radio or game media within a series or season.

episodes.desc: An episode of a TV/radio series or season.

numberOfEpisodes.desc: The number of episodes in this season or series.

numberOfSeasons.desc: The number of seasons in this series.

productionCompany.desc: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

season.desc: A season in a media series.

seasons.desc: A season in a media series.

trailer.desc: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

http://schema.org/Table.desc: A table on a Web page.

http://schema.org/TakeAction.desc:
The act of gaining ownership of an object from an origin. Reciprocal of GiveAction.

Related actions:

* [[GiveAction]]: The reciprocal of TakeAction.
* [[ReceiveAction]]: Unlike ReceiveAction, TakeAction implies that ownership has been transfered.

http://schema.org/TaxiReservation.desc: A reservation for a taxi.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, use [[Offer]].

partySize.desc: Number of people the reservation should accommodate.

pickupLocation.desc: Where a taxi will pick up a passenger or a rental car can be picked up.

pickupTime.desc: When a taxi will pickup a passenger or a rental car can be picked up.

http://schema.org/TaxiService.desc: A service for a vehicle for hire with a driver for local travel. Fares are usually calculated based on distance traveled.

http://schema.org/TechArticle.desc: A technical article - Example: How-to (task) topics, step-by-step, procedural troubleshooting, specifications, etc.

dependencies.desc: Prerequisites needed to fulfill steps in article.

proficiencyLevel.desc: Proficiency needed for this content; expected values: 'Beginner', 'Expert'.

http://schema.org/TelevisionChannel.desc: A unique instance of a television BroadcastService on a CableOrSatelliteService lineup.

http://schema.org/TextDigitalDocument.desc: A file composed primarily of text.

http://schema.org/TheaterGroup.desc: A theater group or company, for example, the Royal Shakespeare Company or Druid Theatre.

http://schema.org/Thing.desc: The most generic type of item.

additionalType.desc: An additional type for the item, typically used for adding more specific types from external vocabularies in microdata syntax. This is a relationship between something and a class that the thing is in. In RDFa syntax, it is better to use the native RDFa syntax - the 'typeof' attribute - for multiple types. Schema.org tools may have only weaker understanding of extra types, in particular those defined externally.

disambiguatingDescription.desc: A sub property of description. A short description of the item used to disambiguate from other, similar items. Information from other properties (in particular, name) may be necessary for the description to be useful for disambiguation.

identifier.desc: The identifier property represents any kind of identifier for any kind of [[Thing]], such as ISBNs, GTIN codes, UUIDs etc. Schema.org provides dedicated properties for representing many of these, either as textual strings or as URL (URI) links. See [background notes](/docs/datamodel.html#identifierBg) for more details.

image.desc: An image of the item. This can be a [[URL]] or a fully described [[ImageObject]].

mainEntityOfPage.desc: Indicates a page (or other CreativeWork) for which this thing is the main entity being described. See [background notes](/docs/datamodel.html#mainEntityBackground) for details.

potentialAction.desc: Indicates a potential Action, which describes an idealized action in which this thing would play an 'object' role.

sameAs.desc: URL of a reference Web page that unambiguously indicates the item's identity. E.g. the URL of the item's Wikipedia page, Wikidata entry, or official website.

subjectOf.desc: A CreativeWork or Event about this Thing..

http://schema.org/Ticket.desc: Used to describe a ticket to an event, a flight, a bus ride, etc.

dateIssued.desc: The date the ticket was issued.

issuedBy.desc: The organization issuing the ticket or permit.

priceCurrency.desc: The currency of the price, or a price component when attached to [[PriceSpecification]] and its subtypes.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

ticketNumber.desc: The unique identifier for the ticket.

ticketToken.desc: Reference to an asset (e.g., Barcode, QR code image or PDF) usable for entrance.

ticketedSeat.desc: The seat associated with the ticket.

totalPrice.desc:
The total price for the reservation or ticket, including applicable taxes, shipping, etc.

Usage guidelines:

* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.

underName.desc: The person or organization the reservation or ticket is for.

http://schema.org/TieAction.desc: The act of reaching a draw in a competitive activity.

http://schema.org/TipAction.desc: The act of giving money voluntarily to a beneficiary in recognition of services rendered.

recipient.desc: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

http://schema.org/TouristAttraction.desc: A tourist attraction.  In principle any Thing can be a [[TouristAttraction]], from a [[Mountain]] and [[LandmarksOrHistoricalBuildings]] to a [[LocalBusiness]].  This Type can be used on its own to describe a general [[TouristAttraction]], or be used as an [[additionalType]] to add tourist attraction properties to any other type.  (See examples below)

availableLanguage.desc: A language someone may use with or at the item, service or place. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[inLanguage]]

touristType.desc: Attraction suitable for type(s) of tourist. eg. Children, visitors from a particular country, etc.

http://schema.org/TrackAction.desc:
An agent tracks an object for updates.

Related actions:

* [[FollowAction]]: Unlike FollowAction, TrackAction refers to the interest on the location of innanimates objects.
* [[SubscribeAction]]: Unlike SubscribeAction, TrackAction refers to  the interest on the location of innanimate objects.

deliveryMethod.desc: A sub property of instrument. The method of delivery.

http://schema.org/TradeAction.desc: The act of participating in an exchange of goods and services for monetary compensation. An agent trades an object, product or service with a participant in exchange for a one time or periodic payment.

price.desc:
The offer price of a product, or of a price component when attached to PriceSpecification and its subtypes.

Usage guidelines:

* Use the [[priceCurrency]] property (with standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR") instead of including [ambiguous symbols](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dollar_sign#Currencies_that_use_the_dollar_or_peso_sign) such as '$' in the value.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.
* Note that both [RDFa](http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-primer/#using-the-content-attribute) and Microdata syntax allow the use of a "content=" attribute for publishing simple machine-readable values alongside more human-friendly formatting.
* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.

priceCurrency.desc: The currency of the price, or a price component when attached to [[PriceSpecification]] and its subtypes.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

priceSpecification.desc: One or more detailed price specifications, indicating the unit price and delivery or payment charges.

http://schema.org/TrainReservation.desc: A reservation for train travel.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, use [[Offer]].

http://schema.org/TrainTrip.desc: A trip on a commercial train line.

arrivalPlatform.desc: The platform where the train arrives.

arrivalStation.desc: The station where the train trip ends.

departurePlatform.desc: The platform from which the train departs.

departureStation.desc: The station from which the train departs.

trainName.desc: The name of the train (e.g. The Orient Express).

trainNumber.desc: The unique identifier for the train.

http://schema.org/TransferAction.desc: The act of transferring/moving (abstract or concrete) animate or inanimate objects from one place to another.

fromLocation.desc: A sub property of location. The original location of the object or the agent before the action.

toLocation.desc: A sub property of location. The final location of the object or the agent after the action.

http://schema.org/TravelAction.desc: The act of traveling from an fromLocation to a destination by a specified mode of transport, optionally with participants.

distance.desc: The distance travelled, e.g. exercising or travelling.

http://schema.org/Trip.desc: A trip or journey. An itinerary of visits to one or more places.

offers.desc: An offer to provide this itemfor example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event.

provider.desc: The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.

http://schema.org/TypeAndQuantityNode.desc: A structured value indicating the quantity, unit of measurement, and business function of goods included in a bundle offer.

amountOfThisGood.desc: The quantity of the goods included in the offer.

businessFunction.desc: The business function (e.g. sell, lease, repair, dispose) of the offer or component of a bundle (TypeAndQuantityNode). The default is http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell.

typeOfGood.desc: The product that this structured value is referring to.

unitCode.desc: The unit of measurement given using the UN/CEFACT Common Code (3 characters) or a URL. Other codes than the UN/CEFACT Common Code may be used with a prefix followed by a colon.

unitText.desc:
A string or text indicating the unit of measurement. Useful if you cannot provide a standard unit code for
unitCode.

http://schema.org/UnRegisterAction.desc:
The act of un-registering from a service.

Related actions:

* [[RegisterAction]]: antonym of UnRegisterAction.
* [[LeaveAction]]: Unlike LeaveAction, UnRegisterAction implies that you are unregistering from a service you werer previously registered, rather than leaving a team/group of people.

http://schema.org/UnitPriceSpecification.desc: The price asked for a given offer by the respective organization or person.

billingIncrement.desc: This property specifies the minimal quantity and rounding increment that will be the basis for the billing. The unit of measurement is specified by the unitCode property.

priceType.desc: A short text or acronym indicating multiple price specifications for the same offer, e.g. SRP for the suggested retail price or INVOICE for the invoice price, mostly used in the car industry.

referenceQuantity.desc: The reference quantity for which a certain price applies, e.g. 1 EUR per 4 kWh of electricity. This property is a replacement for unitOfMeasurement for the advanced cases where the price does not relate to a standard unit.

unitCode.desc: The unit of measurement given using the UN/CEFACT Common Code (3 characters) or a URL. Other codes than the UN/CEFACT Common Code may be used with a prefix followed by a colon.

unitText.desc:
A string or text indicating the unit of measurement. Useful if you cannot provide a standard unit code for
unitCode.

http://schema.org/UpdateAction.desc: The act of managing by changing/editing the state of the object.

collection.desc: A sub property of object. The collection target of the action.

targetCollection.desc: A sub property of object. The collection target of the action.

http://schema.org/UseAction.desc: The act of applying an object to its intended purpose.

http://schema.org/UserBlocks.desc: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

http://schema.org/UserCheckins.desc: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

http://schema.org/UserComments.desc: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

commentTime.desc: The time at which the UserComment was made.

creator.desc: The creator/author of this CreativeWork. This is the same as the Author property for CreativeWork.

discusses.desc: Specifies the CreativeWork associated with the UserComment.

replyToUrl.desc: The URL at which a reply may be posted to the specified UserComment.

http://schema.org/UserDownloads.desc: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

http://schema.org/UserInteraction.desc: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

http://schema.org/UserLikes.desc: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

http://schema.org/UserPageVisits.desc: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

http://schema.org/UserPlays.desc: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

http://schema.org/UserPlusOnes.desc: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

http://schema.org/UserTweets.desc: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

http://schema.org/Vehicle.desc: A vehicle is a device that is designed or used to transport people or cargo over land, water, air, or through space.

cargoVolume.desc:
The available volume for cargo or luggage. For automobiles, this is usually the trunk volume.

Typical unit code(s): LTR for liters, FTQ for cubic foot/feet

Note: You can use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate ranges.

dateVehicleFirstRegistered.desc: The date of the first registration of the vehicle with the respective public authorities.

driveWheelConfiguration.desc: The drive wheel configuration, i.e. which roadwheels will receive torque from the vehicle's engine via the drivetrain.

fuelConsumption.desc:
The amount of fuel consumed for traveling a particular distance or temporal duration with the given vehicle (e.g. liters per 100 km).

* Note 1: There are unfortunately no standard unit codes for liters per 100 km.  Use [[unitText]] to indicate the unit of measurement, e.g. L/100 km.
* Note 2: There are two ways of indicating the fuel consumption, [[fuelConsumption]] (e.g. 8 liters per 100 km) and [[fuelEfficiency]] (e.g. 30 miles per gallon). They are reciprocal.
* Note 3: Often, the absolute value is useful only when related to driving speed ("at 80 km/h") or usage pattern ("city traffic"). You can use [[valueReference]] to link the value for the fuel consumption to another value.

fuelEfficiency.desc:
The distance traveled per unit of fuel used; most commonly miles per gallon (mpg) or kilometers per liter (km/L).

* Note 1: There are unfortunately no standard unit codes for miles per gallon or kilometers per liter. Use [[unitText]] to indicate the unit of measurement, e.g. mpg or km/L.
* Note 2: There are two ways of indicating the fuel consumption, [[fuelConsumption]] (e.g. 8 liters per 100 km) and [[fuelEfficiency]] (e.g. 30 miles per gallon). They are reciprocal.
* Note 3: Often, the absolute value is useful only when related to driving speed ("at 80 km/h") or usage pattern ("city traffic"). You can use [[valueReference]] to link the value for the fuel economy to another value.

fuelType.desc: The type of fuel suitable for the engine or engines of the vehicle. If the vehicle has only one engine, this property can be attached directly to the vehicle.

knownVehicleDamages.desc: A textual description of known damages, both repaired and unrepaired.

mileageFromOdometer.desc: The total distance travelled by the particular vehicle since its initial production, as read from its odometer.\n\nTypical unit code(s): KMT for kilometers, SMI for statute miles

numberOfAirbags.desc: The number or type of airbags in the vehicle.

numberOfAxles.desc: The number of axles.\n\nTypical unit code(s): C62

numberOfDoors.desc: The number of doors.\n\nTypical unit code(s): C62

numberOfForwardGears.desc: The total number of forward gears available for the transmission system of the vehicle.\n\nTypical unit code(s): C62

numberOfPreviousOwners.desc: The number of owners of the vehicle, including the current one.\n\nTypical unit code(s): C62

productionDate.desc: The date of production of the item, e.g. vehicle.

purchaseDate.desc: The date the item e.g. vehicle was purchased by the current owner.

steeringPosition.desc: The position of the steering wheel or similar device (mostly for cars).

vehicleConfiguration.desc: A short text indicating the configuration of the vehicle, e.g. '5dr hatchback ST 2.5 MT 225 hp' or 'limited edition'.

vehicleEngine.desc: Information about the engine or engines of the vehicle.

vehicleIdentificationNumber.desc: The Vehicle Identification Number (VIN) is a unique serial number used by the automotive industry to identify individual motor vehicles.

vehicleInteriorColor.desc: The color or color combination of the interior of the vehicle.

vehicleInteriorType.desc: The type or material of the interior of the vehicle (e.g. synthetic fabric, leather, wood, etc.). While most interior types are characterized by the material used, an interior type can also be based on vehicle usage or target audience.

vehicleModelDate.desc: The release date of a vehicle model (often used to differentiate versions of the same make and model).

vehicleSeatingCapacity.desc: The number of passengers that can be seated in the vehicle, both in terms of the physical space available, and in terms of limitations set by law.\n\nTypical unit code(s): C62 for persons.

vehicleSpecialUsage.desc: Indicates whether the vehicle has been used for special purposes, like commercial rental, driving school, or as a taxi. The legislation in many countries requires this information to be revealed when offering a car for sale.

vehicleTransmission.desc: The type of component used for transmitting the power from a rotating power source to the wheels or other relevant component(s) ("gearbox" for cars).

http://schema.org/VideoGallery.desc: Web page type: Video gallery page.
