http://schema.org/VideoGame.desc: A video game is an electronic game that involves human interaction with a user interface to generate visual feedback on a video device.

actor.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

actors.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

director.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

directors.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

gamePlatform.desc: The electronic systems used to play video games.

gameServer.desc: The server on which  it is possible to play the game.

playMode.desc: Indicates whether this game is multi-player, co-op or single-player.  The game can be marked as multi-player, co-op and single-player at the same time.

trailer.desc: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

http://schema.org/VideoGameClip.desc: A short segment/part of a video game.

actor.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

actors.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

characterAttribute.desc: A piece of data that represents a particular aspect of a fictional character (skill, power, character points, advantage, disadvantage).

containsSeason.desc: A season that is part of the media series.

director.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

directors.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

episode.desc: An episode of a tv, radio or game media within a series or season.

episodes.desc: An episode of a TV/radio series or season.

gameItem.desc: An item is an object within the game world that can be collected by a player or, occasionally, a non-player character.

gameLocation.desc: Real or fictional location of the game (or part of game).

gamePlatform.desc: The electronic systems used to play video games.

numberOfEpisodes.desc: The number of episodes in this season or series.

numberOfPlayers.desc: Indicate how many people can play this game (minimum, maximum, or range).

numberOfSeasons.desc: The number of seasons in this series.

playMode.desc: Indicates whether this game is multi-player, co-op or single-player.  The game can be marked as multi-player, co-op and single-player at the same time.

productionCompany.desc: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

quest.desc: The task that a player-controlled character, or group of characters may complete in order to gain a reward.

season.desc: A season in a media series.

seasons.desc: A season in a media series.

trailer.desc: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

actor.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

actors.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

caption.desc: The caption for this object. For downloadable machine formats (closed caption, subtitles etc.) use MediaObject and indicate the [[encodingFormat]].

director.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

directors.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

thumbnail.desc: Thumbnail image for an image or video.

transcript.desc: If this MediaObject is an AudioObject or VideoObject, the transcript of that object.

videoFrameSize.desc: The frame size of the video.

http://schema.org/ViewAction.desc: The act of consuming static visual content.

http://schema.org/VisualArtwork.desc: A work of art that is primarily visual in character.

artEdition.desc: The number of copies when multiple copies of a piece of artwork are produced - e.g. for a limited edition of 20 prints, 'artEdition' refers to the total number of copies (in this example "20").

artMedium.desc: The material used. (e.g. Oil, Watercolour, Acrylic, Linoprint, Marble, Cyanotype, Digital, Lithograph, DryPoint, Intaglio, Pastel, Woodcut, Pencil, Mixed Media, etc.)

artform.desc: e.g. Painting, Drawing, Sculpture, Print, Photograph, Assemblage, Collage, etc.

artworkSurface.desc: The supporting materials for the artwork, e.g. Canvas, Paper, Wood, Board, etc.

surface.desc: A material used as a surface in some artwork, e.g. Canvas, Paper, Wood, Board, etc.

http://schema.org/VoteAction.desc: The act of expressing a preference from a fixed/finite/structured set of choices/options.

candidate.desc: A sub property of object. The candidate subject of this action.

http://schema.org/WPAdBlock.desc: An advertising section of the page.

http://schema.org/WPFooter.desc: The footer section of the page.

http://schema.org/WPHeader.desc: The header section of the page.

http://schema.org/WPSideBar.desc: A sidebar section of the page.

http://schema.org/WantAction.desc: The act of expressing a desire about the object. An agent wants an object.

http://schema.org/WarrantyPromise.desc: A structured value representing the duration and scope of services that will be provided to a customer free of charge in case of a defect or malfunction of a product.

durationOfWarranty.desc: The duration of the warranty promise. Common unitCode values are ANN for year, MON for months, or DAY for days.

warrantyScope.desc: The scope of the warranty promise.

http://schema.org/WarrantyScope.desc:
A range of of services that will be provided to a customer free of charge in case of a defect or malfunction of a product.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Labor-BringIn
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PartsAndLabor-BringIn
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PartsAndLabor-PickUp

http://schema.org/WatchAction.desc: The act of consuming dynamic/moving visual content.

http://schema.org/WearAction.desc: The act of dressing oneself in clothing.

browserRequirements.desc: Specifies browser requirements in human-readable text. For example, 'requires HTML5 support'.

http://schema.org/WebPage.desc: A web page. Every web page is implicitly assumed to be declared to be of type WebPage, so the various properties about that webpage, such as breadcrumb may be used. We recommend explicit declaration if these properties are specified, but if they are found outside of an itemscope, they will be assumed to be about the page.

breadcrumb.desc: A set of links that can help a user understand and navigate a website hierarchy.

lastReviewed.desc: Date on which the content on this web page was last reviewed for accuracy and/or completeness.

mainContentOfPage.desc: Indicates if this web page element is the main subject of the page.

primaryImageOfPage.desc: Indicates the main image on the page.

relatedLink.desc: A link related to this web page, for example to other related web pages.

reviewedBy.desc: People or organizations that have reviewed the content on this web page for accuracy and/or completeness.

significantLink.desc: One of the more significant URLs on the page. Typically, these are the non-navigation links that are clicked on the most.

significantLinks.desc: The most significant URLs on the page. Typically, these are the non-navigation links that are clicked on the most.

speakable.desc:
Indicates sections of a Web page that are particularly 'speakable' in the sense of being highlighted as being especially appropriate for text-to-speech conversion. Other sections of a page may also be usefully spoken in particular circumstances; the 'speakable' property serves to indicate the parts most likely to be generally useful for speech.

The *speakable* property can be repeated an arbitrary number of times, with three kinds of possible 'content-locator' values:

1.) *id-value* URL references - uses *id-value* of an element in the page being annotated. The simplest use of *speakable* has (potentially relative) URL values, referencing identified sections of the document concerned.

2.) CSS Selectors - addresses content in the annotated page, eg. via class attribute. Use the [[cssSelector]] property.

3.)  XPaths - addresses content via XPaths (assuming an XML view of the content). Use the [[xpath]] property.


For more sophisticated markup of speakable sections beyond simple ID references, either CSS selectors or XPath expressions to pick out document section(s) as speakable. For this
we define a supporting type, [[SpeakableSpecification]]  which is defined to be a possible value of the *speakable* property.

specialty.desc: One of the domain specialities to which this web page's content applies.

http://schema.org/WebPageElement.desc: A web page element, like a table or an image.

cssSelector.desc: A CSS selector, e.g. of a [[SpeakableSpecification]] or [[WebPageElement]]. In the latter case, multiple matches within a page can constitute a single conceptual "Web page element".

xpath.desc: An XPath, e.g. of a [[SpeakableSpecification]] or [[WebPageElement]]. In the latter case, multiple matches within a page can constitute a single conceptual "Web page element".

http://schema.org/WebSite.desc: A WebSite is a set of related web pages and other items typically served from a single web domain and accessible via URLs.

issn.desc: The International Standard Serial Number (ISSN) that identifies this serial publication. You can repeat this property to identify different formats of, or the linking ISSN (ISSN-L) for, this serial publication.

http://schema.org/WinAction.desc: The act of achieving victory in a competitive activity.

loser.desc: A sub property of participant. The loser of the action.

http://schema.org/WorkersUnion.desc: A Workers Union (also known as a Labor Union, Labour Union, or Trade Union) is an organization that promotes the interests of its worker members by collectively bargaining with management, organizing, and political lobbying.

http://schema.org/WriteAction.desc: The act of authoring written creative content.

inLanguage.desc: The language of the content or performance or used in an action. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[availableLanguage]].

language.desc: A sub property of instrument. The language used on this action.
